WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.480
[Amit Varma]: Before you listen to this episode of The Scene and the Unseen, I have a recommendation for

00:00:08.480 --> 00:00:09.480
[Amit Varma]: you.

00:00:09.480 --> 00:00:13.640
[Amit Varma]: Do check out Pulya Bazi, hosted by Saurabh Chandra and Pranay Kotesane, two really good

00:00:13.640 --> 00:00:14.640
[Amit Varma]: friends of mine.

00:00:14.640 --> 00:00:16.680
[Amit Varma]: Kick-ass podcast in Hindi.

00:00:16.680 --> 00:00:17.680
[Amit Varma]: It's amazing.

00:00:17.680 --> 00:00:24.240
[Amit Varma]: In 2014, when the BJP swept the general elections, commentators spoke about the Modi wave.

00:00:24.240 --> 00:00:27.080
[Amit Varma]: Some people were stunned by the size of this wave.

00:00:27.080 --> 00:00:31.600
[Amit Varma]: But maybe they would not have been so surprised if they'd followed the cultural, social and

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:34.000
[Amit Varma]: political currents behind this wave.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:38.920
[Amit Varma]: Narendra Modi's rise to power did not start in 2002 when the Gujarat riots happened, or

00:00:38.920 --> 00:00:43.880
[Amit Varma]: 1992 when the Babri Masjid was demolished in Ayodhya, or even 1980 when the BJP was

00:00:43.880 --> 00:00:44.880
[Amit Varma]: founded.

00:00:44.880 --> 00:00:49.680
[Amit Varma]: These currents, in some form or another, go back decades, if not centuries.

00:00:49.680 --> 00:00:54.800
[Amit Varma]: They started gathering force and were given direction around a century ago, and it was

00:00:54.800 --> 00:01:00.520
[Amit Varma]: such a well-organized, well-thought-out, powerful force that I am surprised that we didn't have

00:01:00.520 --> 00:01:03.160
[Amit Varma]: a Hindu Rashtra long, long ago.

00:01:03.160 --> 00:01:08.160
[Amit Varma]: The book that I will discuss on the show today is ostensibly a book of history, but it will

00:01:08.160 --> 00:01:13.320
[Amit Varma]: reveal the true nature of modern India more than almost any other book you can find in

00:01:13.320 --> 00:01:14.320
[Amit Varma]: the market.

00:01:14.320 --> 00:01:23.120
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:01:23.120 --> 00:01:24.120
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:24.120 --> 00:01:29.000
[Unknown]: Please welcome your host, Amit Bharma.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:30.000
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:34.160
[Amit Varma]: I'm honored to have the journalist and author Akshay Mukul as my guest today, and we'll

00:01:34.160 --> 00:01:38.480
[Amit Varma]: be chatting about his brilliant book, Gita Press and the Making of Hindu India.

00:01:38.480 --> 00:01:44.080
[Amit Varma]: There's been a common question asked in recent years, sometimes with genuine curiosity and

00:01:44.080 --> 00:01:46.120
[Amit Varma]: sometimes with mockery.

00:01:46.120 --> 00:01:48.560
[Amit Varma]: Where are the intellectuals of the right wing?

00:01:48.560 --> 00:01:53.000
[Amit Varma]: I explored this question myself in an episode I did a few months ago called The Intellectual

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:57.280
[Amit Varma]: Foundations of Hindutva, where I chatted with Aakar Patel, who is writing a book on the

00:01:57.280 --> 00:01:58.600
[Amit Varma]: Hindu Rashtra.

00:01:58.600 --> 00:02:03.440
[Amit Varma]: At the end of the episode, Aakar and I concluded that there isn't really much there.

00:02:03.440 --> 00:02:07.480
[Amit Varma]: On reading Akshay's book, I realized that we were perhaps too glib.

00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:11.760
[Amit Varma]: There is an organized intellectual tradition within the Hindutva movement, and there has

00:02:11.760 --> 00:02:15.200
[Amit Varma]: been coherence and consistency over the decades.

00:02:15.200 --> 00:02:19.640
[Amit Varma]: Maybe people like me have discounted it because our first language is English and we don't

00:02:19.640 --> 00:02:24.360
[Amit Varma]: read the Hindi press, and maybe we discounted it because we have such contempt for the founding

00:02:24.360 --> 00:02:28.120
[Amit Varma]: principles of this tradition that we hesitate to call it intellectual.

00:02:28.120 --> 00:02:31.560
[Amit Varma]: Either way, it's our mistake and our loss.

00:02:31.560 --> 00:02:36.680
[Amit Varma]: Without understanding these intellectual currents, I don't believe we can understand India.

00:02:36.680 --> 00:02:41.400
[Amit Varma]: And we will continue to be surprised, election after election, as our elite little bubble

00:02:41.400 --> 00:02:43.480
[Amit Varma]: continues to count for nothing.

00:02:43.480 --> 00:02:49.240
[Amit Varma]: Also, all our talk of getting our ideas into the culture stand for nothing.

00:02:49.240 --> 00:02:54.040
[Amit Varma]: If we cannot understand our culture in the first place, and the forces that shaped it.

00:02:54.040 --> 00:02:57.760
[Amit Varma]: Gita Press and The Making of Hindu India is an eye-opening book.

00:02:57.760 --> 00:03:04.200
[Amit Varma]: But before I begin my conversations with Akshay, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:03:04.200 --> 00:03:08.360
[Amit Varma]: Did you know that Parsis in Mumbai, instead of being left at the Tower of Silence after

00:03:08.360 --> 00:03:10.560
[Amit Varma]: they die, are now cremated?

00:03:10.560 --> 00:03:11.560
[Amit Varma]: And why?

00:03:11.560 --> 00:03:14.040
[Amit Varma]: Because a cow fell sick in the early 1990s?

00:03:14.040 --> 00:03:18.520
[Amit Varma]: Did you know that the smog in Delhi is caused by something that farmers in Punjab do, and

00:03:18.520 --> 00:03:20.760
[Amit Varma]: that there's no way to stop them?

00:03:20.760 --> 00:03:25.360
[Amit Varma]: Did you know that there wasn't one gas tragedy in Bhopal, but three?

00:03:25.360 --> 00:03:27.960
[Amit Varma]: One of them was seen, but two were unseen?

00:03:27.960 --> 00:03:32.640
[Amit Varma]: Did you know that many well-intentioned government policies hurt the people they're supposed

00:03:32.640 --> 00:03:33.840
[Amit Varma]: to help?

00:03:33.840 --> 00:03:36.500
[Amit Varma]: Why was demonetization a bad idea?

00:03:36.500 --> 00:03:38.800
[Amit Varma]: How should GST have been implemented?

00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:44.440
[Amit Varma]: Why are all our politicians so corrupt, when not all of them are bad people?

00:03:44.440 --> 00:03:50.040
[Amit Varma]: I'm Amit Verma, and in my weekly podcast, The Seen and the Unseen, I take a shot at

00:03:50.040 --> 00:03:52.480
[Amit Varma]: answering all these questions and many more.

00:03:52.480 --> 00:03:58.000
[Amit Varma]: I aim to go beyond the scene and show you the unseen effects of public policy and private

00:03:58.000 --> 00:03:59.000
[Amit Varma]: action.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:03.480
[Amit Varma]: I speak to experts on economics, political philosophy, cognitive neuroscience, and constitutional

00:04:03.480 --> 00:04:08.320
[Amit Varma]: law, so that their insights can blow not only my mind, but also yours.

00:04:08.320 --> 00:04:11.400
[Amit Varma]: The Seen and the Unseen releases every Monday.

00:04:11.400 --> 00:04:15.360
[Amit Varma]: So do check out the archives and follow the show at seenunseen.in.

00:04:15.360 --> 00:04:21.080
[Amit Varma]: You can also subscribe to The Seen and the Unseen on whatever podcast app you happen

00:04:21.080 --> 00:04:22.080
[Amit Varma]: to prefer.

00:04:22.080 --> 00:04:27.080
[Amit Varma]: Akshay, welcome to The Seen and the Unseen.

00:04:27.080 --> 00:04:28.080
[Amit Varma]: Thank you, Amit, for having me.

00:04:28.080 --> 00:04:30.880
[Amit Varma]: Akshay, tell me a little bit about yourself.

00:04:30.880 --> 00:04:31.880
[Amit Varma]: How did you become a journalist?

00:04:31.880 --> 00:04:34.000
[Guest]: How did your journey start?

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:35.880
[Guest]: I grew up in Ranchi.

00:04:35.880 --> 00:04:40.280
[Guest]: I'm originally from Bihar, but I grew up in Ranchi, which is now Jharkhand.

00:04:40.280 --> 00:04:45.800
[Guest]: So it was, it's a very cosmopolitan, I grew up in an industrial township.

00:04:45.800 --> 00:04:52.600
[Guest]: And we grew up without getting too much affected by caste or religion, because, you know, for

00:04:52.600 --> 00:04:57.160
[Guest]: years I had Goan neighbors or Garhwali neighbors, because you know, this is how industrial towns

00:04:57.160 --> 00:04:58.640
[Guest]: are.

00:04:58.640 --> 00:05:04.480
[Guest]: And I studied there till my plus two, which is I did intermediate, went to JVS college

00:05:04.480 --> 00:05:05.480
[Guest]: there.

00:05:05.480 --> 00:05:10.600
[Guest]: And then I came to Delhi University, where I studied history, I majored in history.

00:05:10.600 --> 00:05:16.240
[Guest]: And then, well, like everyone from Bihar, or that part of the world, tries a hand at

00:05:16.240 --> 00:05:19.520
[Guest]: civil services, which I did one attempt.

00:05:19.520 --> 00:05:25.480
[Guest]: And then I thought, no, that's something maybe I'm, it's not for me, I just couldn't clear

00:05:25.480 --> 00:05:26.480
[Guest]: it.

00:05:26.480 --> 00:05:28.000
[Guest]: I just couldn't even clear prelims.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:34.360
[Guest]: So I went for, I thought journalism, I tried journalism, I went to IMC.

00:05:34.360 --> 00:05:39.840
[Guest]: And then I joined, I worked four places, started with Asian Age, which was just launched.

00:05:39.840 --> 00:05:44.320
[Unknown]: And it was like talk of the town, it was one of the biggest thing to happen in the early

00:05:44.320 --> 00:05:45.320
[Unknown]: 90s.

00:05:45.320 --> 00:05:51.320
[Unknown]: Then worked in Pioneer for three and a half years, then in a way changed hands.

00:05:51.320 --> 00:05:55.320
[Guest]: Then I moved to Hindustan Times, where I worked for exactly two years.

00:05:55.320 --> 00:05:59.520
[Unknown]: And then Times of India, where I worked for almost 17 years.

00:05:59.520 --> 00:06:02.480
[Unknown]: And then now I kind of quit, now I'm off journalism.

00:06:02.480 --> 00:06:04.880
[Unknown]: I quit in 2017.

00:06:04.880 --> 00:06:08.200
[Unknown]: And since then, I'm kind of on my own now.

00:06:08.200 --> 00:06:10.800
[Amit Varma]: And what kind of journalism attracted you?

00:06:10.800 --> 00:06:17.080
[Guest]: Well, journalism, when I had grown up reading all kinds of journalism, I'm talking of M.

00:06:17.080 --> 00:06:21.520
[Guest]: J. Akbar of those days, not the M. J. Akbar of now, when he was editing Telegraph and

00:06:21.520 --> 00:06:28.160
[Guest]: growing up in Ranchi, and Telegraph was launched, and it was in the paper in Ranchi always normally

00:06:28.160 --> 00:06:30.360
[Guest]: comes in the evening.

00:06:30.360 --> 00:06:32.160
[Guest]: But one waited for that paper.

00:06:32.160 --> 00:06:35.720
[Guest]: And even waited for Indian Express or Times of India, which all came in the evening because

00:06:35.720 --> 00:06:37.840
[Guest]: there were no Patna editions, no other editions.

00:06:37.840 --> 00:06:42.560
[Guest]: So Delhi edition will come by air and will come in the evening.

00:06:42.560 --> 00:06:46.600
[Guest]: One was really attracted to the kind of journalism which was happening those days with, you know,

00:06:46.600 --> 00:06:50.960
[Guest]: Bhagarpur blindings happened, Arun Souri was there, M. J. Akbar was there.

00:06:50.960 --> 00:06:53.920
[Guest]: And these people were taking on the establishment.

00:06:53.920 --> 00:07:01.440
[Guest]: And when I joined profession in late 93, early 94, these people were still there, Arun Souri

00:07:01.440 --> 00:07:07.720
[Guest]: was no longer working in active journalism, but Akbar was, I joined his paper.

00:07:07.720 --> 00:07:12.720
[Guest]: Other people, Chandan Mitra, other people who one had grown up reading.

00:07:12.720 --> 00:07:19.720
[Guest]: So there was this whole thing on this right on the genuine issues of the country, right

00:07:19.720 --> 00:07:22.360
[Guest]: on the politics.

00:07:22.360 --> 00:07:24.920
[Guest]: And it was a phase when Congress was dominating.

00:07:24.920 --> 00:07:30.640
[Guest]: And although it was like the fag end of Congress dominance, but still Congress was very much

00:07:30.640 --> 00:07:33.160
[Guest]: the dominating force.

00:07:33.160 --> 00:07:38.040
[Guest]: And there was this whole larger alliance of anti-Congressism happening, socialists, leftists,

00:07:38.040 --> 00:07:41.240
[Guest]: even BJP, all of them were coming together.

00:07:41.240 --> 00:07:45.080
[Guest]: So it was a very, very interesting phase when I joined journalism.

00:07:45.080 --> 00:07:53.720
[Guest]: I remember in 93, one of the, this 94, in fact, this Andhra election was taking place.

00:07:53.720 --> 00:07:56.360
[Guest]: And this was a one big election.

00:07:56.360 --> 00:08:03.480
[Guest]: I think Chandra Babu Naidu had managed to come back, it was, I remember, it was a big

00:08:03.480 --> 00:08:04.480
[Guest]: election.

00:08:04.480 --> 00:08:08.840
[Guest]: Then, of course, that was a phase of instability, we saw governments after governments come

00:08:08.840 --> 00:08:16.200
[Guest]: and go from 89 onwards, only five years of Narsimha Rao, five stable years of 96, 98,

00:08:16.200 --> 00:08:17.200
[Guest]: 99.

00:08:17.200 --> 00:08:20.600
[Guest]: And then the stability, now we are in a stable phase.

00:08:20.600 --> 00:08:28.000
[Guest]: And once all that, you know, I was in HD when Kargil happened, I covered Kargil in a very

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:29.000
[Guest]: different way.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:36.120
[Guest]: I covered post-Kargil, I traveled, I remember from Meerut to Tehri Garhwal, Pauri Garhwal,

00:08:36.120 --> 00:08:40.640
[Guest]: just talking, going to the families who had lost their children, their sons, brothers,

00:08:40.640 --> 00:08:48.320
[Guest]: you know, husbands, and the whole futility of war, what goes in the family, one could

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:56.600
[Guest]: see it firsthand, and a lot more things are happening in terms of religious politics,

00:08:56.600 --> 00:09:02.680
[Guest]: because you know, 92 was very fresh, 92 had happened, politics had gone for a complete

00:09:02.680 --> 00:09:04.720
[Guest]: chin, Mandal had happened.

00:09:04.720 --> 00:09:13.440
[Guest]: So it was very, very, we saw United Front government, we saw six years of Bajpayee rule,

00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:21.680
[Guest]: 99, and then he again, 98, 14 months, and then five years from 99 to 2004.

00:09:21.680 --> 00:09:28.800
[Guest]: And I covered, I started basically as a feature writer, I was writing on arts and culture.

00:09:28.800 --> 00:09:34.940
[Guest]: And I must have interviewed all the writers, poets, painters, you can think of, because

00:09:34.940 --> 00:09:41.520
[Guest]: Pioneer was the only paper those days, which had a dedicated arts page five days a week.

00:09:41.520 --> 00:09:45.600
[Guest]: And it was a very serious arts page, very, very serious people were writing, very serious

00:09:45.600 --> 00:09:51.280
[Guest]: columnists were there, and we got really into the subject.

00:09:51.280 --> 00:09:56.120
[Guest]: So and then we had a very good weekend paper for which I wrote a lot.

00:09:56.120 --> 00:10:00.120
[Guest]: Then I moved to writing more and more on politics while I was still there.

00:10:00.120 --> 00:10:05.160
[Guest]: And while I moved to HD, it was again part of the Sunday team, but it was writing more

00:10:05.160 --> 00:10:06.160
[Guest]: on politics.

00:10:06.160 --> 00:10:11.520
[Guest]: And that's where I covered, I had a lot of experience doing varied things.

00:10:11.520 --> 00:10:17.200
[Guest]: For instance, I, much before this Gujarat thing, I remember doing a full page on Gujarat

00:10:17.200 --> 00:10:20.080
[Guest]: as Hindutva Laboratory.

00:10:20.080 --> 00:10:25.160
[Guest]: And they were outraged that how he's saying this, and this was way back in 99.

00:10:25.160 --> 00:10:31.560
[Guest]: Then I did on this whole how they were trying to, what they're trying to do with syllabus,

00:10:31.560 --> 00:10:34.360
[Guest]: NCRT syllabus.

00:10:34.360 --> 00:10:39.840
[Guest]: And I remember Murali Manohar Joshi getting very hassled about it, he was HRD minister.

00:10:39.840 --> 00:10:45.280
[Guest]: I did a lot on, I wrote on the Narmada Bachao Andolan, which was in a very crucial phase,

00:10:45.280 --> 00:10:51.240
[Guest]: which was kind of in a way, disintegrating, you know, that was the last rally for the

00:10:51.240 --> 00:10:55.360
[Guest]: valley I remember in 99 or early 2000.

00:10:55.360 --> 00:10:57.440
[Guest]: So we did a lot of interesting stuff.

00:10:57.440 --> 00:11:03.160
[Guest]: And then I came to Daily Grind in Times of India, where I was covering political parties,

00:11:03.160 --> 00:11:09.440
[Guest]: Parliament, I was doing a dedicated ministry, like HRD ministry, or culture ministry, which

00:11:09.440 --> 00:11:14.000
[Guest]: gave you a ringside view of how government functions, what happens, how decisions are

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:17.720
[Guest]: taken or not taken, or made and made.

00:11:17.720 --> 00:11:24.720
[Guest]: And Parliament, of course, teaches you, you see closely how legislation happens, how things

00:11:24.720 --> 00:11:30.360
[Guest]: work, how politicians, how political parties come together on certain issues, how on certain

00:11:30.360 --> 00:11:35.800
[Guest]: issues, whatever might be the rhetoric outside, deep within, they're all together, you know,

00:11:35.800 --> 00:11:38.200
[Guest]: so you see all those things happening very closely.

00:11:38.200 --> 00:11:40.400
[Guest]: So it was a very, very good, very enriching experience.

00:11:40.400 --> 00:11:45.400
[Guest]: And I was lucky to work with some of the very, very good editors, you know, I worked with

00:11:45.400 --> 00:11:52.680
[Unknown]: Bharat Bhushan, I worked with Chandan Mitra, worked with Beer Sanghvi for a while in Hindustan

00:11:52.680 --> 00:11:53.680
[Guest]: Times.

00:11:53.680 --> 00:12:02.240
[Guest]: I had NHD, I had all, Padgaonkar was just kind of the last days of Padgaonkar in Times

00:12:02.240 --> 00:12:03.240
[Guest]: of India.

00:12:03.240 --> 00:12:06.760
[Guest]: But yeah, one knew him, one could always go up to him.

00:12:06.760 --> 00:12:10.520
[Guest]: Then we had people like Siddharth Varadarajan, Manoj Joshi, you know, so it was a very, very

00:12:10.520 --> 00:12:11.520
[Guest]: good.

00:12:11.520 --> 00:12:19.920
[Guest]: Later on, changes happened in Times of India around 2004, early 2004.

00:12:19.920 --> 00:12:25.800
[Guest]: Because somewhere BJP, I think it was a complete coup, a lot of people had to move out and

00:12:25.800 --> 00:12:30.200
[Guest]: the people who was considered very close to the government took over.

00:12:30.200 --> 00:12:35.080
[Guest]: But then the election they lost.

00:12:35.080 --> 00:12:43.240
[Guest]: And after that, and one has actually I consider 2004 and 2009, actually the UPA 2, that's

00:12:43.240 --> 00:12:46.360
[Guest]: when it started deteriorating.

00:12:46.360 --> 00:12:52.400
[Guest]: And now, in 2014, I was very much there when Modi came to power.

00:12:52.400 --> 00:12:57.080
[Guest]: And you could see for the first time, you know, you're always second guessing the your

00:12:57.080 --> 00:13:01.960
[Guest]: boss political bosses, you're thinking what's happening, not happening, which is not to

00:13:01.960 --> 00:13:04.240
[Guest]: say that was not happening during Congress regime.

00:13:04.240 --> 00:13:10.160
[Guest]: I know of Congress ministers who would constantly buzzer editors and owners saying that why

00:13:10.160 --> 00:13:15.920
[Guest]: my particular kind of picture gets published, please ensure that it never comes out again.

00:13:15.920 --> 00:13:17.800
[Guest]: But it's become far worse.

00:13:17.800 --> 00:13:21.840
[Amit Varma]: Now it's happening at a different level, all together.

00:13:21.840 --> 00:13:28.400
[Amit Varma]: I had a young political scientist on my show a few weeks ago called Rahul Verma, and who's

00:13:28.400 --> 00:13:30.960
[Amit Varma]: just written this book called Ideology and Identity.

00:13:30.960 --> 00:13:36.760
[Amit Varma]: And Rahul made a very interesting point that because he grew up essentially reading Hindi

00:13:36.760 --> 00:13:43.400
[Amit Varma]: newspapers every day, he got a very different view of India from what his peers have today.

00:13:43.400 --> 00:13:48.080
[Amit Varma]: I'm just wondering that in your case, you grew up in Ranchi, and obviously, your Hindi

00:13:48.080 --> 00:13:49.760
[Guest]: is excellent, because you know,

00:13:49.760 --> 00:13:54.080
[Guest]: Yeah, my family has been a very bilingual family has been a stress.

00:13:54.080 --> 00:13:56.080
[Guest]: So that's how I got used to Hindi literature.

00:13:56.080 --> 00:14:02.080
[Guest]: I read Hindi literature a lot, when I was growing up, I continue to and I feel we have

00:14:02.080 --> 00:14:08.400
[Guest]: added this completely false sense of I don't know what to call it, but by you know, reading

00:14:08.400 --> 00:14:12.880
[Guest]: Hindi or reading any other language, it's not about Hindi reading, I have Telugu friends

00:14:12.880 --> 00:14:18.600
[Guest]: who are my generation who kind of regret their children not reading, I regret my daughter

00:14:18.600 --> 00:14:21.160
[Guest]: not reading Hindi as much.

00:14:21.160 --> 00:14:23.200
[Guest]: I don't know, maybe I tried too much.

00:14:23.200 --> 00:14:24.360
[Guest]: Maybe I didn't try enough.

00:14:24.360 --> 00:14:25.440
[Guest]: Maybe there's something wrong.

00:14:25.440 --> 00:14:29.480
[Guest]: But I feel very bad that the children all coming up with a single language, English

00:14:29.480 --> 00:14:31.120
[Guest]: speaking people.

00:14:31.120 --> 00:14:32.480
[Guest]: So that way, yes, I was lucky.

00:14:32.480 --> 00:14:37.760
[Guest]: What Rahul told you, he's absolutely right, your sensibilities, your the way you see the

00:14:37.760 --> 00:14:43.960
[Guest]: world completely changes, because Hindi newspapers in the literature introduce you to world,

00:14:43.960 --> 00:14:48.960
[Guest]: which exists in which we and we are not aware of, you know, for instance, say someone reading

00:14:48.960 --> 00:14:56.560
[Guest]: a book like Raag Darbari, I must have read it, I think I was just out of school or something.

00:14:56.560 --> 00:15:01.640
[Guest]: And so nothing after that, nothing shocks you, you know, you feel that, okay, this is

00:15:01.640 --> 00:15:04.080
[Amit Varma]: so true, he was, you know.

00:15:04.080 --> 00:15:08.960
[Guest]: And you realize the power of literature, more than any other work of nonfiction.

00:15:08.960 --> 00:15:09.960
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

00:15:09.960 --> 00:15:10.960
[Unknown]: Absolutely.

00:15:10.960 --> 00:15:16.160
[Amit Varma]: In fact, Rahul and I discussed Raag Darbari also.

00:15:16.160 --> 00:15:22.600
[Guest]: When you see this India that we are inhabiting now, you realize that, oh God, you know, just

00:15:22.600 --> 00:15:29.920
[Guest]: say this how I met Mr. Lal Sughal much, much later, and I just couldn't imagine, yeah,

00:15:29.920 --> 00:15:35.720
[Guest]: he was a man who had a great sense of humour.

00:15:35.720 --> 00:15:40.080
[Guest]: And I was kind of trying to ask him, what is the process?

00:15:40.080 --> 00:15:41.080
[Guest]: How did he?

00:15:41.080 --> 00:15:45.400
[Guest]: He said, you know, I was just, he was an administrator.

00:15:45.400 --> 00:15:51.560
[Guest]: So he had seen India, he had an added perspective, how things work, what happens.

00:15:51.560 --> 00:15:55.520
[Guest]: So he brought everything there and nothing has changed.

00:15:55.520 --> 00:16:00.320
[Guest]: This is the India of Srilal Sughal, Raag Darbari has not changed at all, if you ask me, nothing

00:16:00.320 --> 00:16:01.320
[Amit Varma]: has changed.

00:16:01.320 --> 00:16:04.960
[Amit Varma]: All of those fundamental things, the way the bureaucracy works, the way people think, it's

00:16:04.960 --> 00:16:08.160
[Amit Varma]: just flat out the same.

00:16:08.160 --> 00:16:11.760
[Amit Varma]: So I can't help but ask you that, okay, so, you know, you went to college and you did

00:16:11.760 --> 00:16:13.440
[Amit Varma]: a degree in history.

00:16:13.440 --> 00:16:17.600
[Amit Varma]: And typically people of my generation and earlier generations, what we did a degree

00:16:17.600 --> 00:16:21.520
[Amit Varma]: on we just happened to do it, it wasn't really a real interest, degree karo, uske baad jo

00:16:21.520 --> 00:16:23.280
[Amit Varma]: karna hai karo.

00:16:23.280 --> 00:16:27.240
[Amit Varma]: And but in your case, there is this interesting symmetry that you do a degree in history,

00:16:27.240 --> 00:16:30.400
[Amit Varma]: and you spend these decades in journalism, and then you write this great book of history.

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:36.000
[Guest]: See, I have been a kind of history junkie, I have been kind of, I have been genuinely

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:38.000
[Guest]: interested in history.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:41.920
[Guest]: And in fact, a lot of my friends who are in academics, they always joke that, you know,

00:16:41.920 --> 00:16:47.940
[Guest]: when a new book comes on history, he probably buys or reads before us, you know.

00:16:47.940 --> 00:16:51.000
[Guest]: So I have this, my entire money goes in books.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:52.000
[Guest]: That's all I've done in life.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.480
[Guest]: If someone asks me, I've done nothing, but only bought books.

00:16:54.480 --> 00:16:55.480
[Guest]: Pretty much the same.

00:16:55.480 --> 00:16:56.480
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:16:56.480 --> 00:16:57.480
[Guest]: So nothing.

00:16:57.480 --> 00:16:59.160
[Guest]: I live behind nothing, just books.

00:16:59.160 --> 00:17:03.240
[Guest]: And I have been genuinely interested reading new kinds of history, what is happening worldwide

00:17:03.240 --> 00:17:05.480
[Guest]: new trends.

00:17:05.480 --> 00:17:10.160
[Guest]: And one can see how the history writing also changed the time when I was in college to

00:17:10.160 --> 00:17:16.080
[Guest]: subsequently and then some books completely kind of, like, for instance, this book that

00:17:16.080 --> 00:17:20.680
[Guest]: I'm talking about Francis Corsini's in the public some days, I'm getting not getting

00:17:20.680 --> 00:17:22.920
[Guest]: the title right.

00:17:22.920 --> 00:17:29.600
[Guest]: And then Vasudha Dalmia's book on nationalization of Hindu tradition on Banaras.

00:17:29.600 --> 00:17:36.440
[Guest]: You find that this is saying something which is first time history writing or don't call

00:17:36.440 --> 00:17:40.760
[Guest]: it history, don't call it it's a kind of a literary history of a different kind of things

00:17:40.760 --> 00:17:45.040
[Guest]: which no one bothered about your history books never told you.

00:17:45.040 --> 00:17:50.400
[Guest]: And they're talking about creation of mindsets, how mindsets became what they become, you

00:17:50.400 --> 00:17:52.560
[Guest]: know, what we are seeing now.

00:17:52.560 --> 00:17:59.200
[Guest]: So Vasudha Dalmia's is a great book, which talks of how this whole thing started in a

00:17:59.200 --> 00:18:04.040
[Guest]: city like Banaras, the role of Bharatendu Harishchandra.

00:18:04.040 --> 00:18:06.240
[Guest]: Francis Corsini takes it even forward.

00:18:06.240 --> 00:18:11.880
[Guest]: Charu Gupta comes, who brings out, if you ever thought that Hindi literature was all

00:18:11.880 --> 00:18:18.720
[Guest]: about nationalism or patriotism and everything, she talks of sexuality, obscenity in Hindi

00:18:18.720 --> 00:18:23.160
[Guest]: literature, not literature, she's even talking about journals, and it's a path breaking book

00:18:23.160 --> 00:18:25.120
[Guest]: actually.

00:18:25.120 --> 00:18:29.080
[Guest]: And then you grew up in a place where you see that Gita Press is there all the time,

00:18:29.080 --> 00:18:35.280
[Guest]: you know, in any ordinary Hindu household, they need not be rabidly communal or anything.

00:18:35.280 --> 00:18:40.240
[Guest]: It's a very secular household, it was coming, it was coming for your grandparents, someone

00:18:40.240 --> 00:18:45.200
[Guest]: was reading somewhere, you know, and if you ask anyone, everyone knew about Gita Press

00:18:45.200 --> 00:18:48.400
[Guest]: and everyone had their own story about Gita Press.

00:18:48.400 --> 00:18:53.160
[Guest]: So then you realize, so in fact, before I started working on it, I asked, I remember

00:18:53.160 --> 00:18:58.120
[Guest]: Wendy Doniger, that why did she never work on it?

00:18:58.120 --> 00:19:03.280
[Guest]: She said, well, I'm not interested so much that aspect of this thing, but it's a very

00:19:03.280 --> 00:19:04.640
[Guest]: good idea.

00:19:04.640 --> 00:19:10.600
[Guest]: And just then before that, there's another historian called Ulrich Stark, she did a brilliant

00:19:10.600 --> 00:19:20.040
[Guest]: book on Naval Kishore Press of Lucknow, Kanpur, and it's an amazing book on the history of

00:19:20.040 --> 00:19:21.800
[Guest]: this press.

00:19:21.800 --> 00:19:25.240
[Guest]: So I kept wondering that how come there's nothing in Gita Press, everyone reads about

00:19:25.240 --> 00:19:30.280
[Guest]: Gita Press, and that got me thinking, that got me inside Gita Press.

00:19:30.280 --> 00:19:33.120
[Guest]: And I could easily relate to it.

00:19:33.120 --> 00:19:37.040
[Guest]: In fact, a lot of my friends, in fact, Basudha also asked me this, that how could you relate

00:19:37.040 --> 00:19:38.040
[Guest]: to this?

00:19:38.040 --> 00:19:41.760
[Guest]: I could relate to it also, because as you said, right in the beginning, you know, because

00:19:41.760 --> 00:19:45.920
[Guest]: of reading is multiple things in languages, Hindi.

00:19:45.920 --> 00:19:50.640
[Guest]: So you know, that was not a kind of alien thing, I didn't have any problem thinking

00:19:50.640 --> 00:19:56.400
[Guest]: about working on Gita Press, it was not something, you know, formidable for me.

00:19:56.400 --> 00:20:00.960
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, a book is, I mean, much more than the history of a printing press.

00:20:00.960 --> 00:20:04.920
[Amit Varma]: It's also to me the history of the whole Hindutva movement.

00:20:04.920 --> 00:20:10.600
[Amit Varma]: It's in a sense, bits of it are also a very fascinating sociological study of Marwaris

00:20:10.600 --> 00:20:12.480
[Unknown]: and how their social position changed.

00:20:12.480 --> 00:20:16.320
[Unknown]: And of course, the main people behind the Gita Press were Marwaris.

00:20:16.320 --> 00:20:21.240
[Amit Varma]: And I was staggered at one point when I came across these figures in your book, I'll just

00:20:21.240 --> 00:20:22.500
[Amit Varma]: quote them.

00:20:22.500 --> 00:20:28.680
[Amit Varma]: As of February 2014, 71.9 million copies of the Gita have been sold.

00:20:28.680 --> 00:20:31.000
[Amit Varma]: This is Gita Press applications.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:35.520
[Amit Varma]: For the Ramcharitmanas and other works by Goswami Tulsidas, the figure is 70 million

00:20:35.520 --> 00:20:40.600
[Amit Varma]: copies, while 19 million copies of the Puranas, Upanishads and ancient scriptures have been

00:20:40.600 --> 00:20:41.600
[Amit Varma]: sold.

00:20:41.600 --> 00:20:45.880
[Amit Varma]: Then there are the tracts and monographs on the duties of ideal Hindu women and children,

00:20:45.880 --> 00:20:51.360
[Amit Varma]: of which 94.8 million copies have been sold so far, while more than 65 million copies

00:20:51.360 --> 00:20:57.600
[Amit Varma]: of stories from India's mythic past, biographies of saints and devotional songs have been bought.

00:20:57.600 --> 00:20:58.600
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:20:58.600 --> 00:21:03.280
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, you also, for example, talking about every year they used to bring out these

00:21:03.280 --> 00:21:10.960
[Amit Varma]: special issues and talking about in 1938, they got out Manasankh, which was in Ramcharitmanas.

00:21:10.960 --> 00:21:15.520
[Amit Varma]: And there you write, quote, the very first print run was of 40,600 copies.

00:21:15.520 --> 00:21:22.440
[Amit Varma]: And by late 1983, a total of 5.69 million copies had been printed, a record unparalleled

00:21:22.440 --> 00:21:25.200
[Amit Varma]: in the work of Indian publishing.

00:21:25.200 --> 00:21:26.440
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:21:26.440 --> 00:21:31.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, maybe I should be ashamed of this, but I had no idea that something so...

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:32.000
[Guest]: Well, if you...

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:40.200
[Guest]: See, in fact, there's a friend of mine from Rachi, who grew up differently, that's all

00:21:40.200 --> 00:21:41.200
[Guest]: I tell him.

00:21:41.200 --> 00:21:42.200
[Guest]: I tease him.

00:21:42.200 --> 00:21:43.200
[Guest]: He said, how come I was not aware?

00:21:43.200 --> 00:21:48.560
[Guest]: Then I said, why don't you ask your parents, maybe, ask your mother, she'll be aware of

00:21:48.560 --> 00:21:50.320
[Guest]: it.

00:21:50.320 --> 00:21:51.640
[Guest]: And he said, no, even she won't be aware.

00:21:51.640 --> 00:21:53.120
[Guest]: I said, no, try it.

00:21:53.120 --> 00:21:56.920
[Guest]: Then he found out that, yes, they knew somehow he was not interested.

00:21:56.920 --> 00:21:58.120
[Guest]: His interests lie elsewhere.

00:21:58.120 --> 00:22:00.000
[Guest]: So, you know, it's about...

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:06.200
[Guest]: But you know, I can safely tell you while I was working on it, I have friends across

00:22:06.200 --> 00:22:12.680
[Guest]: who work across professions, you know, friends who are like very in corporate world from

00:22:12.680 --> 00:22:14.320
[Guest]: university years.

00:22:14.320 --> 00:22:18.400
[Guest]: And if you tell them Gita Press, the brand recall itself told me the story that even

00:22:18.400 --> 00:22:21.240
[Guest]: if they don't know anything about Gita Press, they know about it.

00:22:21.240 --> 00:22:24.560
[Guest]: They know of, they've heard of Gita Press.

00:22:24.560 --> 00:22:26.760
[Guest]: And as far as the numbers, even I was staggered.

00:22:26.760 --> 00:22:28.240
[Guest]: And I took it from their website.

00:22:28.240 --> 00:22:30.640
[Guest]: I didn't want to be kind of...

00:22:30.640 --> 00:22:32.640
[Guest]: And their website says it.

00:22:32.640 --> 00:22:39.760
[Guest]: And there won't be any single, in North India at least, any single in the Hindu household

00:22:39.760 --> 00:22:45.480
[Guest]: where, you know, even a scholar who keeps a copy of, say, Ramayana for some study or

00:22:45.480 --> 00:22:50.040
[Guest]: something, he'll say, okay, boss, let's get the Gita Press version, English as well as

00:22:50.040 --> 00:22:51.040
[Guest]: Hindi.

00:22:51.040 --> 00:22:56.280
[Guest]: Even Mahabharata, because it's cleaner, it's well brought out, it's a very high production

00:22:56.280 --> 00:22:57.280
[Guest]: quality.

00:22:57.280 --> 00:23:01.680
[Guest]: All the books have very high production, even Kalyan, very high production quality.

00:23:01.680 --> 00:23:02.680
[Guest]: Kalyan being the magazine.

00:23:02.680 --> 00:23:05.400
[Guest]: Being the journal, yeah, magazine.

00:23:05.400 --> 00:23:13.840
[Guest]: And the idea of also gifting religious texts, if you go to city like Banaras or Gorakhpur,

00:23:13.840 --> 00:23:21.080
[Guest]: you'll find that there is, or even Delhi, the Delhi store in Chandni Chowk, in that

00:23:21.080 --> 00:23:24.760
[Guest]: old Delhi, certain books, if you call up and say, do you have this?

00:23:24.760 --> 00:23:29.000
[Guest]: No, it's just run out of here, you'll have to wait for a week.

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:31.240
[Guest]: And so it constantly sells.

00:23:31.240 --> 00:23:35.240
[Guest]: And then in Ramayana, then they have this thing called what they call Gutka, which is

00:23:35.240 --> 00:23:37.920
[Guest]: basically smaller, miniature version of Ramayana.

00:23:37.920 --> 00:23:43.600
[Guest]: You're on the road, you can't carry the fat volume, so you can read it.

00:23:43.600 --> 00:23:46.160
[Guest]: But that itself sells in lakhs and lakhs.

00:23:46.160 --> 00:23:51.800
[Guest]: And these figures also, don't forget, would be what they export.

00:23:51.800 --> 00:23:58.160
[Guest]: And huge diaspora population relies on, they're the big clientele in this diaspora population,

00:23:58.160 --> 00:24:03.600
[Guest]: because they were the first ones to even think of, I will not say first one, the early ones,

00:24:03.600 --> 00:24:07.960
[Guest]: who in 1934, started an English journal called Kalyan Kalpataru.

00:24:07.960 --> 00:24:10.800
[Guest]: Because they said, well, we have to do something about them.

00:24:10.800 --> 00:24:15.160
[Amit Varma]: In fact, in your book, you've got accounts of various people, both Indians and non-Indians

00:24:15.160 --> 00:24:17.360
[Guest]: writing from abroad.

00:24:17.360 --> 00:24:22.560
[Guest]: And they were trying to track people who could write, even non-Hindus, great scholars of

00:24:22.560 --> 00:24:28.240
[Guest]: Hinduism, Jainism, they were trying to get them to write, to give it that kind of very

00:24:28.240 --> 00:24:30.840
[Amit Varma]: eclectic feel about it.

00:24:30.840 --> 00:24:35.040
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of go back to the starting of it.

00:24:35.040 --> 00:24:40.000
[Amit Varma]: Let's talk about sort of the impetus behind the Gita Press to start off.

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:44.600
[Amit Varma]: And in your book, you mentioned that there are sort of three factors.

00:24:44.600 --> 00:24:45.960
[Amit Varma]: And let's kind of take them one by one.

00:24:45.960 --> 00:24:51.280
[Amit Varma]: And the first factor that you mentioned is the consolidation of Hindi.

00:24:51.280 --> 00:24:54.600
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about, I mean, all of us take Hindi for granted, like it's been

00:24:54.600 --> 00:24:56.160
[Unknown]: there forever.

00:24:56.160 --> 00:25:00.080
[Amit Varma]: But in a sense, Hindi was a political project of its own.

00:25:00.080 --> 00:25:06.680
[Guest]: Yeah, it was because see, this whole movement in which Madan Mohan Malviya played a big

00:25:06.680 --> 00:25:12.920
[Guest]: role, and 1900, which is called the MacDonald moment, which is actually not my corners,

00:25:12.920 --> 00:25:17.200
[Guest]: Alok Rai's corners, which I find absolutely brilliant corners.

00:25:17.200 --> 00:25:22.960
[Guest]: 1900 is when the petition finally leads to something.

00:25:22.960 --> 00:25:26.560
[Guest]: To recognize Hindi as a separate court language.

00:25:26.560 --> 00:25:28.680
[Guest]: Look at that, you know, very smart move.

00:25:28.680 --> 00:25:33.480
[Guest]: Once you change it in court, subsequently, it has its impact, you know, it's, it has

00:25:33.480 --> 00:25:36.200
[Guest]: its ripple effect.

00:25:36.200 --> 00:25:40.080
[Guest]: And a lot of things are happening simultaneously.

00:25:40.080 --> 00:25:46.200
[Guest]: There is the soul, Hindi is now finally found some place at the cost of Persian.

00:25:46.200 --> 00:25:52.440
[Guest]: Then what happens, the print technology is just coming, which is slowly settling down.

00:25:52.440 --> 00:25:58.240
[Guest]: And Marwari's are investors, we find in most in North India, most of the publishing houses

00:25:58.240 --> 00:26:03.440
[Guest]: Marwari's were investing, and for philanthropic reasons too.

00:26:03.440 --> 00:26:04.440
[Guest]: And then Hindi is coming.

00:26:04.440 --> 00:26:11.520
[Guest]: So first quarter of the 20th century is kind of a golden phase of publishing.

00:26:11.520 --> 00:26:16.040
[Guest]: And Hindi journals are coming one after the other, one after the other, English journals

00:26:16.040 --> 00:26:22.800
[Guest]: are also coming, like, firstly, you have this great modern review coming from Calcutta.

00:26:22.800 --> 00:26:27.160
[Guest]: But Ramanand Chatterjee was a completely different sort of person.

00:26:27.160 --> 00:26:29.720
[Guest]: He was also paying for Bisal Bharat.

00:26:29.720 --> 00:26:33.960
[Guest]: Yeah, so in fact, Calcutta became a big center of Hindi publishing.

00:26:33.960 --> 00:26:39.840
[Guest]: So you had Saraswati coming from Calcutta, you had Bisal Bharat, which continued till

00:26:39.840 --> 00:26:40.920
[Guest]: 70s, actually.

00:26:40.920 --> 00:26:46.560
[Guest]: And in those days, in 1930s, late 30s, he was incurring a loss of 70,000 rupees, but

00:26:46.560 --> 00:26:48.040
[Guest]: he was still publishing it.

00:26:48.040 --> 00:26:54.760
[Guest]: So what I'm trying to say is that it was a golden phase of, now, in that all the journals

00:26:54.760 --> 00:27:02.000
[Guest]: which were coming, were very general in nature, mostly literary, say, Saraswati or Bisal Bharat,

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:05.880
[Guest]: it will have a bit of politics, a bit of literature, a bit of poetry, you know, the usual, some

00:27:05.880 --> 00:27:09.000
[Guest]: international news, but very well brought out.

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:14.960
[Guest]: Gita Press, in a way, is the first one which is exclusively devoted to religion.

00:27:14.960 --> 00:27:18.560
[Guest]: There were a few other attempts made.

00:27:18.560 --> 00:27:23.960
[Guest]: And it came also because, you know, Marwari, there has been a churning happening within

00:27:23.960 --> 00:27:31.680
[Guest]: the Marwari world, because there was a section which was not kind of happy with what the

00:27:31.680 --> 00:27:34.920
[Guest]: newfound wealth was doing to the community.

00:27:34.920 --> 00:27:39.120
[Guest]: As it is, as Goenka at one point says, we are being equated with Jews, and you know,

00:27:39.120 --> 00:27:44.340
[Guest]: we have this thing of us, you know, we're taking money, you know, lending on high rate

00:27:44.340 --> 00:27:45.340
[Amit Varma]: of interest.

00:27:45.340 --> 00:27:52.720
[Guest]: And so, there was this churning happening within and there was this, Marwaris were known

00:27:52.720 --> 00:27:57.920
[Guest]: for the ostentatious display of wealth, and the marriages and various other things.

00:27:57.920 --> 00:28:02.920
[Guest]: So there was this two stream like Jamnalal Bajaj you had, GD Birla, whoever, the moderate

00:28:02.920 --> 00:28:03.920
[Guest]: ones.

00:28:03.920 --> 00:28:07.960
[Guest]: To deal with there were two ways, like Jamnalal Bajaj and also just stop doing this, become

00:28:07.960 --> 00:28:08.960
[Guest]: Gandhian.

00:28:08.960 --> 00:28:14.120
[Guest]: There's this other world of Jai Dayal Goenka, Hanuman Prasad Poddar, and also the answer

00:28:14.120 --> 00:28:22.240
[Guest]: lies in going back to our roots, and basically celebrating the Sanatan Dharm.

00:28:22.240 --> 00:28:28.080
[Guest]: And that, you know, Sanatan, this is what we had a great past, which was interrupted by Muslim

00:28:28.080 --> 00:28:30.640
[Guest]: rule and now British rule.

00:28:30.640 --> 00:28:35.760
[Guest]: And so we have to go back to that period when we were doing extremely well in everything,

00:28:35.760 --> 00:28:42.360
[Guest]: you know, science, literature, and that's this whole thing, Kalyan finds a place.

00:28:42.360 --> 00:28:48.160
[Guest]: So one motive was, of course, that introspection for the community, but there was a larger

00:28:48.160 --> 00:28:54.520
[Guest]: good also involved that, you know, the country should go back to its ancient roots.

00:28:54.520 --> 00:28:56.720
[Amit Varma]: And that's when we were kind of doing very well.

00:28:56.720 --> 00:29:02.400
[Amit Varma]: No, and I find it interesting that, you know, in a sense, the political core of both the

00:29:02.400 --> 00:29:06.680
[Amit Varma]: rise of Hindi and the establishment of the Gita Press and Kalyan seems to be the same,

00:29:06.680 --> 00:29:13.240
[Amit Varma]: which is harking back to a mythical past and leaving aside Hindustani, which is this conglomeration

00:29:13.240 --> 00:29:17.800
[Unknown]: of Urdu and Persian and whatever, and creating Hindi for the Hindus, you know.

00:29:17.800 --> 00:29:23.640
[Amit Varma]: And really, like you point out in 1877, Bhartendu Harishchandra gave this speech called Hinni

00:29:23.640 --> 00:29:25.640
[Unknown]: ki unnati par vyakhya hai.

00:29:25.640 --> 00:29:28.600
[Guest]: And from there, of course, he dies young.

00:29:28.600 --> 00:29:33.240
[Amit Varma]: It kind of becomes a political movement and it totally makes sense that then the journal

00:29:33.240 --> 00:29:38.040
[Amit Varma]: which is set up really to take that politics forward beyond just the religious aspect of

00:29:38.040 --> 00:29:41.560
[Amit Varma]: it is in Hindi and it all kind of seems to come together.

00:29:41.560 --> 00:29:48.240
[Amit Varma]: I also found your whole account of the churn in the Marwari community very interesting.

00:29:48.240 --> 00:29:52.760
[Amit Varma]: For example, I'll quote again from your book, with Marwari, quote, with Marwari domination

00:29:52.760 --> 00:29:58.040
[Amit Varma]: of the growth of Indian capitalism in the late 19th and early 20th century, two crucial

00:29:58.040 --> 00:30:00.960
[Amit Varma]: but contradictory things happened, stop quote.

00:30:00.960 --> 00:30:04.440
[Amit Varma]: And one is because they are the trading class and they're looking for profit and all that,

00:30:04.440 --> 00:30:09.320
[Amit Varma]: they become the butt of jokes like the Jews did elsewhere.

00:30:09.320 --> 00:30:14.600
[Amit Varma]: And the second you point out is, you quote a historian who talks about this semi involuntary

00:30:14.600 --> 00:30:15.600
[Amit Varma]: upward mobility.

00:30:15.600 --> 00:30:16.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:30:16.600 --> 00:30:17.600
[Amit Varma]: I know.

00:30:17.600 --> 00:30:18.600
[Amit Varma]: It's fascinating.

00:30:18.600 --> 00:30:21.520
[Amit Varma]: In which Vaishyas become the new Kshatriyas.

00:30:21.520 --> 00:30:27.920
[Guest]: So in fact, you know, because it was a money, cloud of money, you find that Marwaris, if

00:30:27.920 --> 00:30:32.960
[Guest]: you follow Sanatan Dharam for a second, for argument's sake, not that one believes in

00:30:32.960 --> 00:30:38.480
[Guest]: it is that Marwaris had no business to be wearing sacred thread, right?

00:30:38.480 --> 00:30:44.760
[Guest]: But because of the money, you find that their entire ritual got Brahmanized.

00:30:44.760 --> 00:30:58.120
[Guest]: Then you find the temples, schools, the hospitals, you know, sarais, inns, whatever they were

00:30:58.120 --> 00:31:03.160
[Guest]: making, everywhere started bearing plaque of wealthy Marwari who helped in building

00:31:03.160 --> 00:31:05.960
[Guest]: it or repairing it.

00:31:05.960 --> 00:31:06.960
[Guest]: It's not a phenomenon.

00:31:06.960 --> 00:31:09.120
[Guest]: You will not find it a single plaque.

00:31:09.120 --> 00:31:13.920
[Guest]: As one of my historian friends says, pre 20th century period, Marwaris were still coming

00:31:13.920 --> 00:31:14.920
[Guest]: up.

00:31:14.920 --> 00:31:20.000
[Guest]: It's only after around the first quarter of 20th century, that they had to establish themselves

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:25.040
[Guest]: to deal with this infamy that they were being equated with Jews, that, you know, the money

00:31:25.040 --> 00:31:29.600
[Guest]: making thing was becoming a bit of a problem for the community.

00:31:29.600 --> 00:31:33.640
[Guest]: And there was a churning within also, there was this whole thought process that we should

00:31:33.640 --> 00:31:34.640
[Guest]: do something.

00:31:34.640 --> 00:31:40.120
[Guest]: In fact, there's a historian, he's not a historian, he's kind of a chronicler among Marwaris called

00:31:40.120 --> 00:31:46.640
[Guest]: Jamini Barua, who did a completely, I wish someone could have just put it together in

00:31:46.640 --> 00:31:47.640
[Guest]: a very different way.

00:31:47.640 --> 00:31:51.640
[Guest]: He did a book called Main Apni Marwari Jati Se Pyar Karta Hoon.

00:31:51.640 --> 00:31:57.840
[Guest]: And he brings up, I had to kind of really work hard to get that, all those six volumes.

00:31:57.840 --> 00:32:05.040
[Guest]: But he just puts together every single act of philanthropy that Marwaris did till the

00:32:05.040 --> 00:32:08.680
[Guest]: period that he did book and across India.

00:32:08.680 --> 00:32:17.840
[Guest]: So this was very, very important to Marwaris for getting this whole Brahmanical rituals

00:32:17.840 --> 00:32:22.760
[Guest]: in the marriages also, like a lot of my Marwari friends have told me that a lot of rituals

00:32:22.760 --> 00:32:29.960
[Guest]: are completely Brahmanical, which was not happening, say back home in Rajasthan or anything.

00:32:29.960 --> 00:32:31.560
[Guest]: So that that period becomes very crucial.

00:32:31.560 --> 00:32:36.840
[Guest]: A lot of things are happening in the Marwari world, social, business, you know, in their

00:32:36.840 --> 00:32:39.280
[Guest]: business life and the social life.

00:32:39.280 --> 00:32:43.360
[Amit Varma]: So in fact, in your book, you talk about the philanthropy and then you say, quote, through

00:32:43.360 --> 00:32:49.040
[Amit Varma]: such initiatives, Marwaris replaced the aristocracy and wealthy landlords as religious patrons

00:32:49.040 --> 00:32:54.440
[Amit Varma]: and changed the Kshatriya Brahman interface of Hindu society to a Vaishya Brahman interface

00:32:54.440 --> 00:32:58.200
[Amit Varma]: that eventually resulted in the Marwariization of Hinduism, stop quote.

00:32:58.200 --> 00:33:03.400
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that what was really happening here was a marriage of convenience where the

00:33:03.400 --> 00:33:08.440
[Amit Varma]: Brahmans need the patronage of the Marwaris and the Marwaris are buying respectability

00:33:08.440 --> 00:33:09.440
[Unknown]: through this alliance.

00:33:09.440 --> 00:33:10.440
[Unknown]: Absolutely.

00:33:10.440 --> 00:33:11.440
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:33:11.440 --> 00:33:12.440
[Guest]: It was mutual.

00:33:12.440 --> 00:33:18.800
[Guest]: They were trying to help each other and Kshatriyas never had that kind of, you know, they didn't

00:33:18.800 --> 00:33:21.800
[Guest]: really have, they could fight your war, they could fight your battle, but that's it.

00:33:21.800 --> 00:33:26.640
[Unknown]: And in this age, Rajput valor is pointless.

00:33:26.640 --> 00:33:31.260
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting how the proximate impetus for the Gita Press actually comes from a sort

00:33:31.260 --> 00:33:35.640
[Amit Varma]: of an argument within the Marwari community where you talk about how in the oppressive

00:33:35.640 --> 00:33:41.120
[Amit Varma]: Delhi heat of March, April 1926, there's an 8th annual conference of the All India Marwari

00:33:41.120 --> 00:33:43.040
[Amit Varma]: Agarwal Mahasabha.

00:33:43.040 --> 00:33:47.160
[Amit Varma]: And there, there's an argument between JD Birla and Atmaram Khemka and Atmaram Khemka

00:33:47.160 --> 00:33:50.720
[Amit Varma]: is talking about Sanatan Dharma and this is the direction we should go in.

00:33:50.720 --> 00:33:53.320
[Amit Varma]: And JD Birla is saying, look, this is not the platform for that.

00:33:53.320 --> 00:33:55.500
[Guest]: If you want, why don't you do a journal?

00:33:55.500 --> 00:33:57.200
[Guest]: And that's how this journal comes about.

00:33:57.200 --> 00:34:01.800
[Guest]: And then they have a train journey, Rohtak and all that happens.

00:34:01.800 --> 00:34:06.640
[Guest]: So it's actually fascinating to come to and look at this larger network of Marwaris also

00:34:06.640 --> 00:34:07.640
[Guest]: how they're helping out.

00:34:07.640 --> 00:34:15.120
[Guest]: See, the idea takes place somewhere in, you know, what is Haryana and Bajaj Press, the

00:34:15.120 --> 00:34:21.200
[Guest]: family in Bombay, which are like the big publishers, they still apparently own the big mainland

00:34:21.200 --> 00:34:25.880
[Guest]: money, the press land, because what they had from those days, they had a paper also, Benkatesh

00:34:25.880 --> 00:34:29.520
[Guest]: Samachar or something, and they were big publishers in those days.

00:34:29.520 --> 00:34:35.840
[Guest]: And he agrees to just do it for a year, just take my press, do it, I think almost 14 months

00:34:35.840 --> 00:34:36.840
[Amit Varma]: he did it.

00:34:36.840 --> 00:34:42.760
[Guest]: And meanwhile, Goenka is in Calcutta, Anuman Prasad Poddar is the one who then he moves

00:34:42.760 --> 00:34:46.520
[Guest]: to after, when he moves to Gorakhpur, he moves to Gorakhpur.

00:34:46.520 --> 00:34:47.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:34:47.520 --> 00:34:48.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:34:48.520 --> 00:34:51.760
[Amit Varma]: These are two of the impetuses, which kind of two of the stimuli which made the Gita

00:34:51.760 --> 00:34:52.760
[Amit Varma]: Press happen.

00:34:52.760 --> 00:34:56.800
[Amit Varma]: One, the growth of Hindi as a political movement, and then within the culture as a language

00:34:56.800 --> 00:35:01.540
[Amit Varma]: that people speak and write in, and of course, this Marwari movement where they are getting

00:35:01.540 --> 00:35:07.880
[Amit Varma]: more integrated into that mainstream of Hinduism with their so called, with their putative

00:35:07.880 --> 00:35:09.720
[Amit Varma]: alliance with the Brahmins.

00:35:09.720 --> 00:35:14.920
[Amit Varma]: The third element that you point out is that the 1920s are a hotbed of political communalism.

00:35:14.920 --> 00:35:19.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, like you write about how there were 91 Hindu Muslim riots in United Provinces

00:35:19.840 --> 00:35:23.160
[Amit Varma]: between 1923 and 1927.

00:35:23.160 --> 00:35:29.320
[Amit Varma]: And it's a memorable time because Savarkar's Hindutva comes out in 1923, the RSS is founded

00:35:29.320 --> 00:35:31.760
[Amit Varma]: in 1925.

00:35:31.760 --> 00:35:36.420
[Amit Varma]: And also, which is, you know, the Hindu Mahasabha is a very powerful party at this time, much

00:35:36.420 --> 00:35:39.960
[Amit Varma]: more so then than it is today.

00:35:39.960 --> 00:35:45.440
[Amit Varma]: And also within the Congress, there is a very strong stream of Hindu traditionalists like

00:35:45.440 --> 00:35:46.440
[Guest]: Madan Mohan Malviya.

00:35:46.440 --> 00:35:50.880
[Guest]: And who was also a member of Hindu Mahasabha, you're a member of Congress also.

00:35:50.880 --> 00:35:52.560
[Amit Varma]: Founded the Banaras Hindu University.

00:35:52.560 --> 00:35:57.800
[Amit Varma]: Just lay out that political landscape for me of the time and where sort of Hindu nationalism

00:35:57.800 --> 00:35:58.800
[Guest]: fits in.

00:35:58.800 --> 00:36:07.440
[Guest]: See, they were, I think, till late 19, I think somewhere till 1930s, meeting of Gorakshini

00:36:07.440 --> 00:36:14.360
[Guest]: Sabha and Congress, Hindu Mahasabha and all the members, you could be a member of both.

00:36:14.360 --> 00:36:19.440
[Guest]: So Congress, when it now regrets and says, doesn't actually look back at its past, especially

00:36:19.440 --> 00:36:28.120
[Guest]: very dominant class within the Congress, Nehru and Gandhi's, they managed to battle this

00:36:28.120 --> 00:36:31.280
[Guest]: group, this dominant class within the party.

00:36:31.280 --> 00:36:32.560
[Guest]: But they were always there.

00:36:32.560 --> 00:36:39.800
[Guest]: You know, you have Malviya, you had Govind Ballopant, much later, you had Govind Das.

00:36:39.800 --> 00:36:45.760
[Guest]: So, you know, there's this whole stream of people who were very aligned to the Hindu

00:36:45.760 --> 00:36:46.760
[Guest]: cause.

00:36:46.760 --> 00:36:50.960
[Guest]: But they also knew Congress was the party which had a future.

00:36:50.960 --> 00:36:57.160
[Amit Varma]: I was fascinated by one of the nuggets in your book that back in 1891, a Gaurakshini

00:36:57.160 --> 00:37:00.280
[Amit Varma]: Sabha meeting took place during the Nagpur session of Congress.

00:37:00.280 --> 00:37:01.280
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah.

00:37:01.280 --> 00:37:08.080
[Guest]: It was, see, in fact, if you look at the records, I remember this one, which leader says he

00:37:08.080 --> 00:37:12.960
[Guest]: came out and this person who's reporting is saying he came out after giving a fiery speech

00:37:12.960 --> 00:37:17.280
[Guest]: in the Congress session and walked straight into the Gaurakshini Sabha.

00:37:17.280 --> 00:37:18.280
[Guest]: What do you expect?

00:37:18.280 --> 00:37:24.160
[Guest]: So, now, when today Congress says what it does, they don't know about their own past.

00:37:24.160 --> 00:37:25.840
[Guest]: Actually, some of them don't.

00:37:25.840 --> 00:37:31.040
[Guest]: Even now, in fact, the problem of Congress is even now you have that element which exists.

00:37:31.040 --> 00:37:35.600
[Guest]: You know, this whole conundrum about whether to go to temple or not to go to temple, Rahul

00:37:35.600 --> 00:37:38.640
[Guest]: Gandhi is a Janavdhari Hindu or not.

00:37:38.640 --> 00:37:39.640
[Guest]: Come on.

00:37:39.640 --> 00:37:45.220
[Guest]: So, this emanates from the past that they have, you know, and one should name names

00:37:45.220 --> 00:37:50.120
[Guest]: in the party in the Congress, but we know who are these leaders who are constantly pushing.

00:37:50.120 --> 00:37:55.320
[Guest]: So, in fact, someone should ask Rahul Gandhi, his whole decision to be a Janav or this temple

00:37:55.320 --> 00:38:01.160
[Guest]: hopping, was it something which he approved of or was someone telling him to do it?

00:38:01.160 --> 00:38:05.280
[Amit Varma]: But I guess the thing with, for example, the so-called soft Hindutva of the Congress today

00:38:05.280 --> 00:38:10.960
[Amit Varma]: is that a lot of it seems to be merely posturing, while back in the day, a lot of the big leaders

00:38:10.960 --> 00:38:11.960
[Guest]: of the Hindu Nationalist movement.

00:38:11.960 --> 00:38:13.720
[Guest]: Yeah, because they were very important leaders.

00:38:13.720 --> 00:38:20.760
[Guest]: Just see the battle that Nehru had to wage with Purushottam Das Tandon on cow.

00:38:20.760 --> 00:38:27.280
[Guest]: Then he says, I'll resign and only someone like Nehru who had to really believe in what

00:38:27.280 --> 00:38:28.280
[Amit Varma]: he did.

00:38:28.280 --> 00:38:34.440
[Amit Varma]: And another battle, in fact, which Nehru lost is when the idol of Lord Ram appears magically

00:38:34.440 --> 00:38:40.080
[Amit Varma]: in the Singh and Gobind Mallapant is then CM of UP, Lal Bahadur Shastri is Home Minister

00:38:40.080 --> 00:38:44.280
[Amit Varma]: of UP and he tells him, get the idol removed and they ignore him.

00:38:44.280 --> 00:38:45.280
[Guest]: They ignore.

00:38:45.280 --> 00:38:48.600
[Guest]: Look at Rajeshwar Dayal's account when he says that nobody would listen to him.

00:38:48.600 --> 00:38:50.040
[Unknown]: He was Home Secretary.

00:38:50.040 --> 00:38:54.160
[Guest]: And even in case of Poddar, Poddar is among thousands of people.

00:38:54.160 --> 00:38:56.320
[Guest]: Nobody's saying whether he was directly involved or not.

00:38:56.320 --> 00:39:01.840
[Guest]: But yes, he was also who was suspected to have some role in Gandhi's assassination.

00:39:01.840 --> 00:39:08.800
[Guest]: How on earth someone who was arrested even for a few days in 48, in 51, will you recommend

00:39:08.800 --> 00:39:11.800
[Amit Varma]: him for Bharat Ratna?

00:39:11.800 --> 00:39:13.560
[Guest]: Which Govind Mallapant did.

00:39:13.560 --> 00:39:14.560
[Guest]: It's unimaginable.

00:39:14.560 --> 00:39:19.440
[Guest]: But how could he even suggest and then you're saying you tear off this later.

00:39:19.440 --> 00:39:20.440
[Guest]: That anyway was a tradition.

00:39:20.440 --> 00:39:24.360
[Guest]: Those everyone used to say, tell everyone, tear off the letter and none of them did,

00:39:24.360 --> 00:39:25.360
[Amit Varma]: you know.

00:39:25.360 --> 00:39:28.520
[Amit Varma]: And now we come to the hero of the story, Hanuman Prasad Poddar, who is, of course,

00:39:28.520 --> 00:39:32.480
[Amit Varma]: a cultural giant, which is why I think Govind Mallapant would have wanted to give him the

00:39:32.480 --> 00:39:33.520
[Amit Varma]: Bharat Ratna.

00:39:33.520 --> 00:39:38.160
[Amit Varma]: But he's also somewhat like Gandhi, a figure with many internal contradictions.

00:39:38.160 --> 00:39:40.440
[Guest]: He is at one level, he's a fascinating man.

00:39:40.440 --> 00:39:45.280
[Guest]: You really want to, he never went to university, he never went to, I mean, if you read his

00:39:45.280 --> 00:39:52.280
[Guest]: English, it's impeccable, you see his range of readings, it's impeccable.

00:39:52.280 --> 00:39:57.380
[Guest]: He was a fascinating editor, he was an editor who could go out of the way to, if you see

00:39:57.380 --> 00:40:01.960
[Guest]: his letters to some of these contributors, someone teaching at Hunter College in New

00:40:01.960 --> 00:40:08.520
[Guest]: York, his writing and he's not, he's just, he's relentless that you have to write.

00:40:08.520 --> 00:40:15.000
[Guest]: And his whole knowledge about who's working on what all over the world is fascinating.

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:18.640
[Guest]: Even the new-age sadhus who are coming up in a big way in Germany, who are teaching

00:40:18.640 --> 00:40:21.480
[Guest]: yoga, he's aware of all of them.

00:40:21.480 --> 00:40:27.440
[Guest]: He is, the way he gets after Sampoornanand, he says, you have to, I'll keep the issue

00:40:27.440 --> 00:40:30.440
[Guest]: on hold, but you have to write.

00:40:30.440 --> 00:40:31.600
[Guest]: And he lets him write.

00:40:31.600 --> 00:40:37.400
[Guest]: And when Sampoornanand, as a chief minister, writes something which is not to his liking,

00:40:37.400 --> 00:40:41.120
[Guest]: he says, well, we'll publish it once, but we won't want any further debate on it.

00:40:41.120 --> 00:40:42.400
[Guest]: And he makes it very clear.

00:40:42.400 --> 00:40:50.440
[Guest]: So if you, from his point of view, he was an editor for more than 40 years, 46 years.

00:40:50.440 --> 00:40:54.840
[Guest]: And mind you, in between, many times he'll throw tantrums, he'll leave, he'll go away,

00:40:54.840 --> 00:40:56.160
[Guest]: but they'll never let him go away.

00:40:56.160 --> 00:40:59.120
[Guest]: He became larger than life.

00:40:59.120 --> 00:41:03.600
[Guest]: And on top of that, he had this whole spiritual aspect to him that he had visions of God and

00:41:03.600 --> 00:41:04.600
[Amit Varma]: this and that.

00:41:04.600 --> 00:41:05.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, which is very interesting.

00:41:05.600 --> 00:41:08.480
[Amit Varma]: I mean, there was a soul origin myth about how he was born.

00:41:08.480 --> 00:41:09.480
[Guest]: Yeah, everything.

00:41:09.480 --> 00:41:10.720
[Guest]: So he was created.

00:41:10.720 --> 00:41:16.680
[Guest]: So you know, they address him in a certain way in Gorakhpur.

00:41:16.680 --> 00:41:19.520
[Guest]: So he's seen as an incarnation of God.

00:41:19.520 --> 00:41:25.880
[Guest]: I know people who, I know one lady who's like now 90 plus, coming from a big industrialist

00:41:25.880 --> 00:41:30.120
[Guest]: family in Delhi, who just couldn't believe, who thought that I was doing a great work

00:41:30.120 --> 00:41:33.600
[Guest]: of God by writing on Gita Press.

00:41:33.600 --> 00:41:39.240
[Guest]: And the kind of things that she had to say about Podar, because Podar, people saw, those

00:41:39.240 --> 00:41:43.040
[Guest]: who believed in him, saw him no less than as an incarnation of God.

00:41:43.040 --> 00:41:46.640
[Guest]: In fact, you quote Teji Bachchan in your book.

00:41:46.640 --> 00:41:47.640
[Guest]: Yeah, Teji Bachchan.

00:41:47.640 --> 00:41:50.640
[Guest]: Imagine one of the birthdays, I think seventh birthday of Ajitabh Bachchan, he's brought

00:41:50.640 --> 00:41:53.680
[Guest]: all the way to Gorakhpur.

00:41:53.680 --> 00:41:59.640
[Guest]: And then he did the Avadhi Gita, only at the instance of Radha Baba, who was like his guru

00:41:59.640 --> 00:42:01.640
[Amit Varma]: and later.

00:42:01.640 --> 00:42:09.320
[Amit Varma]: This was, yeah, and just to quote like two different, very different aspects of Podar

00:42:09.320 --> 00:42:13.560
[Amit Varma]: and both unrelated to sort of his professional work, but personal aspects, which I found

00:42:13.560 --> 00:42:14.560
[Amit Varma]: fascinating.

00:42:14.560 --> 00:42:17.020
[Amit Varma]: And the first one is, of course, a spooky religious aspect.

00:42:17.020 --> 00:42:21.080
[Amit Varma]: And you write, quote, Podar would have more visions of God in the next few years.

00:42:21.080 --> 00:42:26.840
[Amit Varma]: In 1936, he claimed to have been met in Gita Vatika, which was where he lived, by celestials,

00:42:26.840 --> 00:42:31.280
[Amit Varma]: a sage Narada and Angiras, the sage who received the Atharva Veda.

00:42:31.280 --> 00:42:37.360
[Amit Varma]: Podar claimed that they explained to him concepts which are not part of the Shastras, stop quote.

00:42:37.360 --> 00:42:41.960
[Amit Varma]: And another aspect of it, which is a more introspective, self-critical aspect, which

00:42:41.960 --> 00:42:46.960
[Amit Varma]: you write about later in the book, start quote, writing to an acquaintance, Podar said he

00:42:46.960 --> 00:42:49.840
[Amit Varma]: was not the person he had been made out to be by others.

00:42:49.840 --> 00:42:54.800
[Amit Varma]: And neither was Gita Press anymore the ideal place to seek spiritual solace.

00:42:54.800 --> 00:42:59.000
[Amit Varma]: And now it's Podar's words, till a few years ago, this was a good place for those involved

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:00.560
[Amit Varma]: in spiritual exercise.

00:43:00.560 --> 00:43:06.400
[Amit Varma]: This place is not fulfilling, as it is marked by demonic traits like self-promotion, jealousy,

00:43:06.400 --> 00:43:07.400
[Amit Varma]: materialism.

00:43:07.400 --> 00:43:11.920
[Amit Varma]: And he continues, there is no limit to my meanness and misdemeanors.

00:43:11.920 --> 00:43:17.560
[Amit Varma]: Neither could I become a good person, nor could I help my associates improve, stop quote.

00:43:17.560 --> 00:43:25.120
[Guest]: He will get into these long phases of self-introspection where he will, all his replies to everyone

00:43:25.120 --> 00:43:29.480
[Guest]: would be of this nature, you know, I have failed, I am here.

00:43:29.480 --> 00:43:34.240
[Guest]: And mostly this will be when he'll be in Dalmia's factory in one place, or he'll be in Ratangarh

00:43:34.240 --> 00:43:35.240
[Guest]: in Bikaner.

00:43:35.240 --> 00:43:42.760
[Guest]: This also, in a way, helped building what we call now, you know, Podar brand, you know,

00:43:42.760 --> 00:43:47.160
[Guest]: because people would know that there'll be phases, now Bhaiji, as he was called, Bhaiji

00:43:47.160 --> 00:43:50.080
[Guest]: has gone into sulk or Bhaiji is in a different mode.

00:43:50.080 --> 00:43:53.800
[Guest]: So he's become inaccessible.

00:43:53.800 --> 00:44:01.040
[Guest]: But when he's talking about this whole decline, the moral values in Gita Press, that is mostly

00:44:01.040 --> 00:44:06.400
[Guest]: because he could see what was happening around in his own family, what was happening with

00:44:06.400 --> 00:44:11.640
[Guest]: children, not his children, but, you know, associates, the children, they were going

00:44:11.640 --> 00:44:16.480
[Guest]: out eating, then he has problems with people going watching cinema, people eating ice cream,

00:44:16.480 --> 00:44:21.320
[Guest]: people sharing, drinking from the same glass, which they still continue to kind of propagate,

00:44:21.320 --> 00:44:22.320
[Guest]: you know.

00:44:22.320 --> 00:44:29.200
[Amit Varma]: So, before we get on to sort of the Gita Press itself, how it grew, and one by one we'll

00:44:29.200 --> 00:44:34.120
[Amit Varma]: tackle all the themes, the broad themes that come up, there was an intriguing sidelight,

00:44:34.120 --> 00:44:38.160
[Amit Varma]: which was, you write about this thing called the Roda Conspiracy, which this is well before

00:44:38.160 --> 00:44:41.360
[Guest]: the Gita Press around 1950s, 1960s, when he was growing up in Calcutta, when he was growing

00:44:41.360 --> 00:44:46.360
[Unknown]: up and some Marwaris were involved in this, he himself was arrested.

00:44:46.360 --> 00:44:49.480
[Amit Varma]: And it's very interesting that the Marwaris managed to hush up the matter and they get

00:44:49.480 --> 00:44:53.720
[Amit Varma]: him out and then they almost seem to take a decision as a community that we are not

00:44:53.720 --> 00:44:56.000
[Amit Varma]: going to get into this kind of politics.

00:44:56.000 --> 00:44:59.840
[Amit Varma]: We are going to do our dhandu and all of that.

00:44:59.840 --> 00:45:07.200
[Amit Varma]: And my question is that, is this also to some extent, one of the many reasons that the Hindutva

00:45:07.200 --> 00:45:12.240
[Amit Varma]: movement was never anti-colonial, like later when the Gita Press got into politics, it

00:45:12.240 --> 00:45:17.960
[Amit Varma]: got into politics against fellow nationalists, you know, against Nehru and against the Congress,

00:45:17.960 --> 00:45:19.800
[Guest]: that never against a British person.

00:45:19.800 --> 00:45:24.800
[Guest]: Because see, for them, commerce was, nothing came before commerce.

00:45:24.800 --> 00:45:29.800
[Guest]: It was for commerce that they left their family, wife, children, everyone behind Rajasthan.

00:45:29.800 --> 00:45:32.320
[Guest]: This community was very focused.

00:45:32.320 --> 00:45:37.640
[Guest]: And despite all the joke and whatever, you know, this larger thing which was said about

00:45:37.640 --> 00:45:41.560
[Guest]: Marwaris, that didn't deter them from the path.

00:45:41.560 --> 00:45:45.440
[Guest]: And here comes something which would have completely destroyed them.

00:45:45.440 --> 00:45:50.760
[Guest]: If you see the pages of Kolkata Samachar, which was edited by Jhaber Mal Sharma, who

00:45:50.760 --> 00:45:57.640
[Guest]: was also Marwari, they first tried to, because I was trying to track what they're saying,

00:45:57.640 --> 00:46:00.960
[Guest]: because it was very important what Kolkata Samachar says.

00:46:00.960 --> 00:46:05.200
[Guest]: So they're saying, kuch Marwariyon ki giraftari hui hai, and then they give names, GD Birla

00:46:05.200 --> 00:46:10.640
[Guest]: is also there, one of them, by the way, and who absconded.

00:46:10.640 --> 00:46:15.000
[Guest]: And people say that he went to Ooty and fellow Marwaris who got arrested, they said that

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:19.240
[Guest]: those days, apparently, more than a lakh was paid.

00:46:19.240 --> 00:46:20.240
[Guest]: Can you believe it?

00:46:20.240 --> 00:46:21.240
[Guest]: What the money would be?

00:46:21.240 --> 00:46:22.240
[Amit Varma]: Now, crores, easily.

00:46:22.240 --> 00:46:29.760
[Guest]: And that gentleman, that police officer, later on, which is even more interesting, I think

00:46:29.760 --> 00:46:36.480
[Guest]: Medha's biography of Birla says, he or someone else wrote it that that gentleman, police

00:46:36.480 --> 00:46:43.600
[Guest]: officer later, after retirement from police, was heading the London operations.

00:46:43.600 --> 00:46:51.560
[Guest]: So this immediately, so first thing they did was, they just said that, okay, listen, it

00:46:51.560 --> 00:46:57.760
[Guest]: was not even, their tone was not defiant at all, that, you know, my community has done,

00:46:57.760 --> 00:47:01.480
[Guest]: my boys cannot do it, even if they do it for the larger, no, no, no, nothing.

00:47:01.480 --> 00:47:06.320
[Guest]: They said, basically, they're saying these are misguided youth, okay.

00:47:06.320 --> 00:47:12.360
[Guest]: And then they get certain people who are very close to the colonial rulers to come and speak

00:47:12.360 --> 00:47:17.400
[Guest]: to them, and be there, kind of negotiate on their behalf.

00:47:17.400 --> 00:47:22.320
[Guest]: And the Kolkata Samachar, for the after that is constantly talking about how law abiding

00:47:22.320 --> 00:47:23.320
[Guest]: they are.

00:47:23.320 --> 00:47:25.840
[Guest]: They have nothing to do with all this.

00:47:25.840 --> 00:47:30.000
[Guest]: And as you said, just do your commerce, that they didn't want interrupted at all, which

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:35.200
[Guest]: road arms, if you actually look at the original records, which is there in the sixth volume,

00:47:35.200 --> 00:47:41.480
[Guest]: which West Bengal government brought out, it's like they were really trying to get after

00:47:41.480 --> 00:47:42.480
[Guest]: them.

00:47:42.480 --> 00:47:47.920
[Guest]: But it got hushed, only he and then the gentleman who later became a member of Rajya Sabha,

00:47:47.920 --> 00:47:52.120
[Guest]: Prabhu Dayal Himmat Singh and few others got arrested, their lives.

00:47:52.120 --> 00:47:57.440
[Guest]: So there was a rancor among some of these Marwadis that Birla got away, we still had

00:47:57.440 --> 00:48:00.040
[Guest]: to face punishment, spend time in jail.

00:48:00.040 --> 00:48:03.440
[Amit Varma]: No, I mean, Himmat Singh was a post-independence minister, you know.

00:48:03.440 --> 00:48:04.440
[Guest]: Minister.

00:48:04.440 --> 00:48:09.280
[Guest]: Himmat Singh became one of the top notch lawyers in the country.

00:48:09.280 --> 00:48:16.160
[Guest]: So yes, that was basically keep away from all this, from whatever is happening.

00:48:16.160 --> 00:48:20.960
[Amit Varma]: And this is, you know, also interesting because Poddar, you know, before this, he got very

00:48:20.960 --> 00:48:25.520
[Amit Varma]: influenced by the extremists within the Congress party, as you point out, Bipin Chandra Pal

00:48:25.520 --> 00:48:26.600
[Amit Varma]: and so on.

00:48:26.600 --> 00:48:30.880
[Amit Varma]: And he also simultaneously and later on in time and through the years, this became a

00:48:30.880 --> 00:48:36.040
[Amit Varma]: love-hate relationship, but got extremely close to Gandhi, very close to Gandhi.

00:48:36.040 --> 00:48:40.880
[Amit Varma]: And we'll discuss that as well in the second half, it's really, that relationship is fascinating.

00:48:40.880 --> 00:48:47.160
[Amit Varma]: But what seems to me is that after this Roda thing happens and they are let off, he pretty

00:48:47.160 --> 00:48:51.280
[Amit Varma]: much decides that I'm going to stay away from politics and the Gita Press is really a cultural

00:48:51.280 --> 00:48:52.280
[Amit Varma]: thing.

00:48:52.280 --> 00:48:57.200
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, it's a political project which is happening under the surface.

00:48:57.200 --> 00:49:02.800
[Guest]: And which he makes, his very first editorial of Kalyan in 1926, it's a fascinating, which

00:49:02.800 --> 00:49:07.840
[Guest]: is a kind of a template from which Gita Press has not wavered at all, where he talks of

00:49:07.840 --> 00:49:12.160
[Guest]: everything, where he talks about what is happening all over the world, he's talking about what

00:49:12.160 --> 00:49:17.120
[Guest]: is Hindu-Muslim unity, he's talking about what we should do to...

00:49:17.120 --> 00:49:22.680
[Guest]: And mostly it doesn't become, it doesn't have anti-colonial language.

00:49:22.680 --> 00:49:24.600
[Guest]: It's mostly about the community.

00:49:24.600 --> 00:49:30.200
[Guest]: It's mostly about the religion and Muslims, of course.

00:49:30.200 --> 00:49:34.560
[Guest]: And then he says that, you know, we should learn from Muslims to be together and fight

00:49:34.560 --> 00:49:35.560
[Guest]: together.

00:49:35.560 --> 00:49:43.240
[Guest]: And then he says, he uses the word Sangbal, which is unity of strength.

00:49:43.240 --> 00:49:48.040
[Amit Varma]: In fact, at different points in time, he almost sort of cozy's up to the British.

00:49:48.040 --> 00:49:53.160
[Amit Varma]: For example, when George V dies in 1926, you know, again, quoting from your book, his death

00:49:53.160 --> 00:49:58.000
[Amit Varma]: in 1926 came at a time when Kalyan was still finding its feet and for a journal that counted

00:49:58.000 --> 00:50:03.360
[Amit Varma]: Hindu nationalism as a scenic one of the freedom movement, paying tribute to King George V

00:50:03.360 --> 00:50:07.560
[Amit Varma]: was possibly a calculated act to win the goodwill of the colonial government.

00:50:07.560 --> 00:50:14.640
[Amit Varma]: Poddar called George V an ideal husband, father, son, and friend, and justified the gloom his

00:50:14.640 --> 00:50:18.040
[Amit Varma]: death had brought to his subjects, family, and friends.

00:50:18.040 --> 00:50:20.920
[Unknown]: How would he know George V was an ideal father?

00:50:20.920 --> 00:50:21.920
[Unknown]: That was a...

00:50:21.920 --> 00:50:22.920
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:50:22.920 --> 00:50:23.920
[Unknown]: Randomly...

00:50:23.920 --> 00:50:24.920
[Unknown]: Kuch bhi bolte the.

00:50:24.920 --> 00:50:25.920
[Unknown]: Kuch bhi bolte.

00:50:25.920 --> 00:50:26.920
[Amit Varma]: Do whatever to please them.

00:50:26.920 --> 00:50:31.320
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you know, and as a project gets underway, I mean, you write about how gradually the

00:50:31.320 --> 00:50:36.720
[Amit Varma]: early issues of Kalyan are sort of a testing ground for what become leet motifs and dominant

00:50:36.720 --> 00:50:41.120
[Amit Varma]: themes later, like cow slaughter and gender and so on, which we'll discuss as we go along.

00:50:41.120 --> 00:50:48.400
[Amit Varma]: But I was particularly struck by how, even though the Gita Press and Kalyan was, you'd

00:50:48.400 --> 00:50:52.360
[Amit Varma]: put it in the philanthropic box of the Marwaris that they are not doing this for profit.

00:50:52.360 --> 00:50:53.680
[Amit Varma]: This doesn't mean dhando.

00:50:53.680 --> 00:50:58.800
[Amit Varma]: Nevertheless, you described that the model of Hinduism they sell is almost a Baniya model

00:50:58.800 --> 00:50:59.800
[Amit Varma]: in your words.

00:50:59.800 --> 00:51:00.800
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:51:00.800 --> 00:51:01.800
[Guest]: Baniya model...

00:51:01.800 --> 00:51:06.560
[Guest]: See, they had to make religion attractive.

00:51:06.560 --> 00:51:11.160
[Guest]: One of the ways in which they started right in the beginning, and which in a way played

00:51:11.160 --> 00:51:19.920
[Guest]: a big role, and continues to in fact, is that selling you recite God's name for 20, 50,000

00:51:19.920 --> 00:51:25.320
[Guest]: times, or you write in a notebook and submit to us, they had the Ramayana Bank and all

00:51:25.320 --> 00:51:26.320
[Guest]: that.

00:51:26.320 --> 00:51:32.720
[Guest]: And then they had this Ram Nam, Jab Bibhag, and then similar thing for something for Gita.

00:51:32.720 --> 00:51:40.760
[Guest]: So it immediately struck a chord among people, among the literate people, that, okay, I know

00:51:40.760 --> 00:51:48.200
[Guest]: people who even now are doing it, sending the notebooks full of Ram, Ram, Ram, Ram,

00:51:48.200 --> 00:51:53.600
[Guest]: and they're sending it and they're saying, okay, we've written 100,000 times or...

00:51:53.600 --> 00:51:57.920
[Guest]: So it brought God and directly, you know, there's a direct interface with God.

00:51:57.920 --> 00:52:02.960
[Guest]: And then they said, then this Bhagwan Mahima Ankh, they brought out of Kalyan, which is

00:52:02.960 --> 00:52:09.640
[Guest]: a fascinating issue where everyone is talking about bizarre things have happened because

00:52:09.640 --> 00:52:13.120
[Guest]: they believed in God, and they recited the name of the God.

00:52:13.120 --> 00:52:18.600
[Guest]: And so many times, or they did this, and it helped someone's daughter's marriage two days

00:52:18.600 --> 00:52:25.000
[Guest]: before marriage, someone postman brings 20,000 rupees from somewhere, you know, all kinds

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:26.000
[Guest]: of things.

00:52:26.000 --> 00:52:28.400
[Amit Varma]: And it's almost a transactional model of Hinduism.

00:52:28.400 --> 00:52:29.400
[Guest]: Yeah, it was a very transactional.

00:52:29.400 --> 00:52:31.960
[Guest]: You jump a name enough times, you will get it.

00:52:31.960 --> 00:52:34.120
[Guest]: You do it, you will get it.

00:52:34.120 --> 00:52:40.160
[Guest]: And they'll say, therefore, the stress on whole rituals, that, you know, if you want

00:52:40.160 --> 00:52:46.480
[Guest]: a male child, you have to do this, you know, if you want to do that, you have to have fast

00:52:46.480 --> 00:52:50.400
[Guest]: in the first hour of on certain day.

00:52:50.400 --> 00:52:57.800
[Guest]: And so, and you find that this is even now Kalyan has a full page, which says in the

00:52:57.800 --> 00:53:04.320
[Guest]: coming month, the next month, what will be the celestial positions of and what can you

00:53:04.320 --> 00:53:12.320
[Guest]: do and which is and there are every day some Purnima or some Ekadasi or some Dwadasi, if

00:53:12.320 --> 00:53:19.600
[Guest]: you go by it, and people are following if I have seen women in Gorakhpur, who are kind

00:53:19.600 --> 00:53:25.320
[Guest]: of doing it all the time, and even outside Gorakhpur, you know, you know, women who are

00:53:25.320 --> 00:53:26.320
[Amit Varma]: doing it.

00:53:26.320 --> 00:53:31.600
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I was also, you know, going to discuss a sort of the strategic genius of Poddar and

00:53:31.600 --> 00:53:36.960
[Amit Varma]: the various things they did about outreach, which include the Gita Sabhas, Ramayana Sabhas,

00:53:36.960 --> 00:53:41.000
