[Amit Varma]: In fact, there's a sentence that I remember from your book where you write about how you

00:57:45.800 --> 00:57:48.800
[Amit Varma]: quote someone saying wars have been fought over cows and women.

00:57:48.800 --> 00:57:49.800
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:57:49.800 --> 00:57:54.520
[Guest]: And cow was, because cow was a rallying point for them.

00:57:54.520 --> 00:58:01.760
[Guest]: Cow, they realized, would help them tide over the deep caste divisions, which the Hindus

00:58:01.760 --> 00:58:02.760
[Guest]: had.

00:58:02.760 --> 00:58:06.560
[Guest]: It would help them talk of, not talk of other things.

00:58:06.560 --> 00:58:11.680
[Guest]: And mind you, when this Gaurakshini Sabha started and the violence started in the name

00:58:11.680 --> 00:58:15.600
[Guest]: of cow, Marwaris were bankrolling, but who were the foot soldiers?

00:58:15.600 --> 00:58:21.040
[Guest]: Those soldiers were people like, the communities like Yadavs and Kurmis.

00:58:21.040 --> 00:58:28.080
[Guest]: In fact, if you see in a place like Bihar, some of the riots that took place around that

00:58:28.080 --> 00:58:34.640
[Guest]: period, most of the perpetrators, Hindu perpetrators were the Yadavs.

00:58:34.640 --> 00:58:40.960
[Guest]: So it created a kind of, and cow became a very easy symbol for them.

00:58:40.960 --> 00:58:49.400
[Guest]: And only when you find, only in the 90s or late 80s, early 90s, after the Mandal happened,

00:58:49.400 --> 00:58:53.760
[Guest]: that we find for some time that cow, although the cow movement has been constant, it has

00:58:53.760 --> 00:59:01.160
[Guest]: been going on, but we find that the Ram temple or something came as a rallying point, but

00:59:01.160 --> 00:59:03.400
[Guest]: otherwise cow has been constant.

00:59:03.400 --> 00:59:10.680
[Guest]: In fact, when 2014, these people came to power, Kalyan talked in detail about, and then Maharashtra

00:59:10.680 --> 00:59:11.680
[Guest]: government banned it.

00:59:11.680 --> 00:59:14.440
[Guest]: One of the earliest states in 2014 to do it.

00:59:14.440 --> 00:59:15.440
[Guest]: They were very happy.

00:59:15.440 --> 00:59:18.320
[Guest]: They said, now it should be done across India.

00:59:18.320 --> 00:59:22.400
[Guest]: It should be banned across India and there's this whole thing.

00:59:22.400 --> 00:59:24.400
[Guest]: Why only few states are doing it?

00:59:24.400 --> 00:59:32.480
[Guest]: So it was since 1951 election also, every election when they tell readers who to vote,

00:59:32.480 --> 00:59:33.600
[Guest]: they don't mention a party.

00:59:33.600 --> 00:59:38.880
[Guest]: They only say that just vote for a party which will do these, you know, one, two, three things.

00:59:38.880 --> 00:59:46.280
[Guest]: So this has been a very, very, cow has been the most important symbol or the most sacred

00:59:46.280 --> 00:59:53.520
[Guest]: of things on which they have kind of worked and Gita Press has a big role to play also

00:59:53.520 --> 00:59:59.000
[Guest]: because the cross linkages that Gita Press created among other groups, there were a lot

00:59:59.000 --> 01:00:04.840
[Guest]: of other groups exclusively working for cow, cow protection and other things.

01:00:04.840 --> 01:00:09.520
[Guest]: And that famous, the 60s, the cow protection movement, which led to attack on parliament,

01:00:09.520 --> 01:00:12.440
[Guest]: actually Poddar was at the helm of it.

01:00:12.440 --> 01:00:15.280
[Guest]: He was a treasurer for a long time.

01:00:15.280 --> 01:00:23.280
[Guest]: And Gita, Kalyan was kind of, if you see Kalyan of that time, it was spewing venom.

01:00:23.280 --> 01:00:25.840
[Amit Varma]: And as you pointed out, they had two special issues on cow.

01:00:25.840 --> 01:00:34.240
[Guest]: One was a cow ankh, which was later on, which happened in the, much later, it was kind of.

01:00:34.240 --> 01:00:37.840
[Amit Varma]: And I was trying to figure out why is the cow sacred to Hinduism and you quote Peter

01:00:37.840 --> 01:00:43.600
[Amit Varma]: Vandermeer in your book, where again, I'll quote from your book, Peter Vandermeer asked

01:00:43.600 --> 01:00:47.720
[Amit Varma]: the question, why would people want to die and kill for the protection of cow?

01:00:47.720 --> 01:00:50.120
[Amit Varma]: He looks at the centrality of the cow at four levels.

01:00:50.120 --> 01:00:55.200
[Amit Varma]: One in Brahmanical rituals, a cow is akin to mother or symbol of the earth, the nourisher,

01:00:55.200 --> 01:00:59.200
[Amit Varma]: goddess who fulfills every wish, symbol of wealth and good fortune, Lakshmi, who is integral

01:00:59.200 --> 01:01:01.000
[Amit Varma]: to ritual, blah, blah, blah, blah.

01:01:01.000 --> 01:01:06.640
[Amit Varma]: Two, sacredness is also attached to cow products like milk, dung, and urine.

01:01:06.640 --> 01:01:10.680
[Amit Varma]: Consumption of milk, butter, and ghee is believed to make a person sattvic and a mixture of

01:01:10.680 --> 01:01:15.840
[Amit Varma]: five cow products, milk, curd, butter, urine, and dung is used to prepare the panchgavya

01:01:15.840 --> 01:01:20.960
[Amit Varma]: that is used to purify a polluted person, parenthesis, it was offered as a solution

01:01:20.960 --> 01:01:26.200
[Amit Varma]: for Hindu women who had lost their modesty during the communal riots at the time of partition.

01:01:26.200 --> 01:01:29.520
[Amit Varma]: And we stop parenthesis and we'll come back to this when we talk about gender.

01:01:29.520 --> 01:01:33.440
[Amit Varma]: Three, the symbol of cow as a wish-fulfilling mother of Krishna is celebrated in the bhakti

01:01:33.440 --> 01:01:34.440
[Amit Varma]: cult.

01:01:34.440 --> 01:01:39.200
[Amit Varma]: And finally, Gau Mata was symbolic of both family and community, protecting the cow meant

01:01:39.200 --> 01:01:43.520
[Amit Varma]: reiterating the patriarchal authority like the kingdom of Rama, which is the Ram Rajya,

01:01:43.520 --> 01:01:45.920
[Amit Varma]: the ideal Hindu state, stop quote.

01:01:45.920 --> 01:01:52.520
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting that once we gain independence and India sort of goes in a different direction,

01:01:52.520 --> 01:01:57.880
[Amit Varma]: you also talk about how cow protection arguments begin to be framed in secular terms, such

01:01:57.880 --> 01:02:03.600
[Amit Varma]: as, you know, where you, for example, how they talk about the cow's high economic utility,

01:02:03.600 --> 01:02:08.960
[Amit Varma]: they talk about the relationship between the quality of cattle in general prosperity.

01:02:08.960 --> 01:02:12.880
[Amit Varma]: You talk about how national pride is associated with economic prosperity, which is brought

01:02:12.880 --> 01:02:14.600
[Amit Varma]: about by cows.

01:02:14.600 --> 01:02:20.920
[Amit Varma]: And also about how the cow can cement harmonious relationships between Hindus and Muslims.

01:02:20.920 --> 01:02:26.000
[Guest]: See some of these people had they been alive and seen what was happening now, what is happening

01:02:26.000 --> 01:02:29.440
[Guest]: now in the name of cow, I'm sure they wouldn't have approved of it.

01:02:29.440 --> 01:02:35.800
[Guest]: Because whatever they were doing, they were very clear that, you know, the cow is alive,

01:02:35.800 --> 01:02:40.360
[Guest]: how do you get rid of the cow, which is old, ailing and died on its own?

01:02:40.360 --> 01:02:45.320
[Guest]: Okay, nobody, even if you're not selling it to a slaughterhouse, everyone knew what was

01:02:45.320 --> 01:02:46.800
[Guest]: happening to cow.

01:02:46.800 --> 01:02:52.400
[Guest]: But they knew the skin was being used, the body parts or whatever, you know, various

01:02:52.400 --> 01:02:57.440
[Guest]: ways it's being used, and they were aware of the economic aspect of the whole thing.

01:02:57.440 --> 01:03:01.200
[Guest]: Even Rajendra Prasad, when he's writing in Goa, he's talking about it.

01:03:01.200 --> 01:03:07.280
[Guest]: And he's saying that, let them die on their own, or don't give to slaughterhouse.

01:03:07.280 --> 01:03:11.920
[Guest]: And they're constantly they'll invoke example of Saudi Arabia or one of these countries

01:03:11.920 --> 01:03:14.480
[Guest]: and they'll say, oh, cows are not slaughtered even there.

01:03:14.480 --> 01:03:19.400
[Guest]: And the example of Humayun or Bawar, one of these.

01:03:19.400 --> 01:03:20.400
[Guest]: Now what is happening?

01:03:20.400 --> 01:03:28.080
[Guest]: I don't think the killing, I don't know whether they're approving or maybe if I had this kind

01:03:28.080 --> 01:03:33.240
[Guest]: of, I had, you know, the kind of government we have now, the full Hindu government been

01:03:33.240 --> 01:03:36.080
[Guest]: in power, maybe it would have happened, one doesn't know.

01:03:36.080 --> 01:03:41.160
[Guest]: But that generation was aware of that there has to be some, you know, resolution to this

01:03:41.160 --> 01:03:42.160
[Guest]: whole cow thing.

01:03:42.160 --> 01:03:48.040
[Guest]: When a cow is giving me milk, helping me in various ways, at the end of it, what to do

01:03:48.040 --> 01:03:55.360
[Guest]: with cow, old ailing cow, can a farmer afford five old ailing cow and have new ones also?

01:03:55.360 --> 01:03:56.360
[Guest]: Impossible.

01:03:56.360 --> 01:04:00.440
[Guest]: So there was a way and they were aware of it, what was happening, otherwise, how a slaughterhouse

01:04:00.440 --> 01:04:04.080
[Guest]: is working and how were Hindus running the slaughterhouses.

01:04:04.080 --> 01:04:09.440
[Guest]: And in some of these areas where this movement was very, very strong, Western UP and other

01:04:09.440 --> 01:04:16.920
[Guest]: places, I know in Maharashtra, for instance, although these Podar and all worked very kind

01:04:16.920 --> 01:04:22.880
[Guest]: of actively to close many slaughterhouses, in Bombay, they had this huge slaughterhouse

01:04:22.880 --> 01:04:30.360
[Guest]: which got closed in those days, I think in the 50s, in Bengal, they got certain slaughterhouses

01:04:30.360 --> 01:04:32.480
[Guest]: closed.

01:04:32.480 --> 01:04:37.160
[Guest]: But they had some model that, you know, you do, you have a pasture land, you do this,

01:04:37.160 --> 01:04:39.840
[Guest]: at least that's what they talk.

01:04:39.840 --> 01:04:43.840
[Guest]: Since they were never in power in those days, one doesn't know how it would have kind of

01:04:43.840 --> 01:04:47.960
[Guest]: panned out, but I don't know whether they were approved or what is happening now.

01:04:47.960 --> 01:04:52.440
[Amit Varma]: No, and some of the sort of narratives that came up around the cow seem quite goofy.

01:04:52.440 --> 01:04:57.760
[Amit Varma]: For example, you quote someone called Prabhudhat Dhramacharya, who prescribed a tenfold path

01:04:57.760 --> 01:05:00.160
[Amit Varma]: for Hindus and Hindutva to survive.

01:05:00.160 --> 01:05:04.320
[Amit Varma]: And quoting you, quote, he asked Hindus to keep cows at home, even if this meant they

01:05:04.320 --> 01:05:06.160
[Amit Varma]: had to have fewer motor vehicles.

01:05:06.160 --> 01:05:12.720
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, stop quoting, try telling a modern bhakta dad, but the funniest thing that I found was

01:05:12.720 --> 01:05:14.000
[Amit Varma]: a Vanaspati controversy.

01:05:14.000 --> 01:05:15.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, Vanaspati.

01:05:15.000 --> 01:05:16.840
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit about that.

01:05:16.840 --> 01:05:23.760
[Unknown]: See, Vanaspati, this is a vegetable oil which sort of replaced ghee as a cooking medium.

01:05:23.760 --> 01:05:29.960
[Guest]: So there was this, you know, there's this famous Jain Vanaspati case, which happened

01:05:29.960 --> 01:05:35.320
[Guest]: sometime in the 80s, this news, I think, broken by a journalist, I think Manoj Mitta played

01:05:35.320 --> 01:05:42.240
[Guest]: a big role in it, where this whole beef tallow, which was being used, and some of the Marwadis

01:05:42.240 --> 01:05:47.320
[Guest]: were involved, this class, this community was involved.

01:05:47.320 --> 01:05:53.560
[Guest]: And when the time when they're getting very involved with it, you find that Gita Press

01:05:53.560 --> 01:05:58.120
[Guest]: suddenly turns very business, it's like a business weekly, monthly, where they even

01:05:58.120 --> 01:06:05.000
[Guest]: listing out early days, they were talking of making this distinction between the companies

01:06:05.000 --> 01:06:09.160
[Guest]: which use beef tallow and not beef tallow, this is what the controversy that I'm talking

01:06:09.160 --> 01:06:11.080
[Guest]: about happened much later.

01:06:11.080 --> 01:06:16.920
[Guest]: And they listed out the companies, which were mostly the Marwadi owned companies, which

01:06:16.920 --> 01:06:17.920
[Amit Varma]: were

01:06:17.920 --> 01:06:18.920
[Amit Varma]: In fact, the first one was Gita Press.

01:06:18.920 --> 01:06:25.040
[Guest]: Later on, they had to leave this business, they abandoned this business, because something

01:06:25.040 --> 01:06:28.440
[Guest]: happened, something very controversial, which they will not talk about.

01:06:28.440 --> 01:06:33.840
[Guest]: So when it came to, you know, their business, they use Gita Press to the hilt, especially

01:06:33.840 --> 01:06:38.840
[Guest]: in when in a crisis like this Vanaspati ghee controversy.

01:06:38.840 --> 01:06:41.720
[Guest]: So it was used by them.

01:06:41.720 --> 01:06:46.540
[Guest]: In fact, and then they what they did also on Vanaspati, or controversy, they got more

01:06:46.540 --> 01:06:51.040
[Guest]: and more people to write on it, you know, and when it suited, they used Gandhi, you

01:06:51.040 --> 01:06:52.040
[Amit Varma]: know.

01:06:52.040 --> 01:06:56.520
[Amit Varma]: So in fact, there's again, a quote from your book where Gandhi summarizes an article by

01:06:56.520 --> 01:07:00.280
[Unknown]: Dattar Singh, who is Gandhi's grandfather.

01:07:00.280 --> 01:07:05.520
[Amit Varma]: And he was also a prominent, he was a cow consultant for the government.

01:07:05.520 --> 01:07:10.400
[Amit Varma]: And quoting again from your book, quote, Gandhi summarized Singh's article for wider dissemination.

01:07:10.400 --> 01:07:15.400
[Amit Varma]: Vanaspati, he said, is a poor substitute for ghee, but due to the great margin of profit

01:07:15.400 --> 01:07:21.960
[Amit Varma]: in this industry, its production has developed from 26,000 tons per annum in 1937 to 105,000

01:07:21.960 --> 01:07:23.680
[Amit Varma]: tons in 1943.

01:07:23.680 --> 01:07:28.840
[Amit Varma]: Such rapid growth of the Vanaspati industry, Gandhi feared, will not only adversely affect

01:07:28.840 --> 01:07:33.520
[Amit Varma]: the welfare of the cultivators, but will have a deleterious effect on the cattle industry

01:07:33.520 --> 01:07:38.760
[Amit Varma]: upon which the prosperity of the whole nation directly depends, and it almost sounds like

01:07:38.760 --> 01:07:44.280
[Amit Varma]: Basia Scandal Maker's petition that, you know, block out the South.

01:07:44.280 --> 01:07:48.520
[Amit Varma]: And another interesting thing that I didn't know about, though, I consider myself fairly

01:07:48.520 --> 01:07:54.160
[Amit Varma]: well informed on Indian politics was the whole sort of the cow slaughter agitations of the

01:07:54.160 --> 01:08:01.520
[Amit Varma]: 60s, which came to a head as you point out on 7 November 1966, where Delhi witnessed

01:08:01.520 --> 01:08:06.920
[Amit Varma]: a surge of people estimated between 125,000 and 700,000.

01:08:06.920 --> 01:08:11.840
[Amit Varma]: And among the people who addressed the crowd in front of Parliament were people like Golwalkar,

01:08:11.840 --> 01:08:17.480
[Amit Varma]: Karpatri Maharaj, Prabhudad Brahmachari, Seth Govindas of the Congress, Atal Bihari Vajpayee

01:08:17.480 --> 01:08:18.840
[Guest]: and Hanuman Prasad Puldhar.

01:08:18.840 --> 01:08:25.240
[Guest]: Hanuman Prasad Puldhar was actually the treasurer of that, Goraksha Mahaviyan Samiti.

01:08:25.240 --> 01:08:29.280
[Guest]: He was a very, very important person, in fact.

01:08:29.280 --> 01:08:36.160
[Guest]: I also mentioned somewhere, I think here only when I talk about cow, how RSS Kader, he's

01:08:36.160 --> 01:08:41.120
[Guest]: thanking Golwalkar saying that how your Kader helped our people train and all that, because

01:08:41.120 --> 01:08:45.440
[Guest]: of this whole violence which happened and the way they attacked the city, especially

01:08:45.440 --> 01:08:52.640
[Guest]: this Lutyens Delhi got really attacked, Kamaraj's house got vandalized.

01:08:52.640 --> 01:08:59.360
[Amit Varma]: Some of his staff got beaten up, and they would always play the victim.

01:08:59.360 --> 01:09:03.960
[Guest]: So even every time there was a riot, they would be like, oh, the Muslims started it.

01:09:03.960 --> 01:09:08.960
[Guest]: Even in this they played victim, but for a change with Indira Gandhi, they were like,

01:09:08.960 --> 01:09:12.120
[Guest]: for some time they were really, they didn't know that this is the kind of actions she's

01:09:12.120 --> 01:09:13.120
[Guest]: going to take.

01:09:13.120 --> 01:09:18.640
[Guest]: She didn't know that a lot of people who were arrested and in Tihar jail will get beaten

01:09:18.640 --> 01:09:19.640
[Guest]: up.

01:09:19.640 --> 01:09:23.960
[Guest]: So either police did it or fellow prisoners were asked to beat them up, which is a normal

01:09:23.960 --> 01:09:26.760
[Guest]: practice in jails, in Indian jails.

01:09:26.760 --> 01:09:28.480
[Guest]: That kind of really rattled them.

01:09:28.480 --> 01:09:30.960
[Guest]: They never thought that this will go on for so long.

01:09:30.960 --> 01:09:36.920
[Guest]: So you find this almost what they were doing during the national movement or later during

01:09:36.920 --> 01:09:40.120
[Guest]: emergency, very apologetic tone.

01:09:40.120 --> 01:09:46.840
[Guest]: They're almost writing to Indira Gandhi saying that, addressing her sister, that no, we didn't

01:09:46.840 --> 01:09:49.240
[Guest]: do this, we got, you got it wrong.

01:09:49.240 --> 01:09:52.840
[Guest]: And the movement completely disappears.

01:09:52.840 --> 01:09:59.040
[Guest]: And because the government created its own kind of committee and said, we are doing this

01:09:59.040 --> 01:10:02.120
[Guest]: and they got somehow trapped into this.

01:10:02.120 --> 01:10:07.920
[Guest]: So the movement more or less dies in the aftermath of that much later again.

01:10:07.920 --> 01:10:11.560
[Guest]: And therefore you find there is a period of lull on cow movement, although these groups

01:10:11.560 --> 01:10:17.800
[Guest]: were constantly working and if you go to places like Rishikesh, Vrindavan, Mathura, Banaras,

01:10:17.800 --> 01:10:23.760
[Guest]: you find these groups existed, but they'd lost that, although Gita Press continued to

01:10:23.760 --> 01:10:24.760
[Guest]: talk about it.

01:10:24.760 --> 01:10:27.600
[Guest]: Gita Press in its journal will talk and all that.

01:10:27.600 --> 01:10:31.840
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, so just kind of thinking about that, like you said that in politics, the

01:10:31.840 --> 01:10:36.320
[Amit Varma]: cow issue waxed and waned and, you know, now it's back, of course, but Gita Press kept

01:10:36.320 --> 01:10:38.240
[Amit Varma]: talking about it throughout.

01:10:38.240 --> 01:10:44.200
[Amit Varma]: Was it something like, did they genuinely expect cow slaughter to at some point in time

01:10:44.200 --> 01:10:51.600
[Amit Varma]: be banned across the country, or was it more of a rhetorical tool to mobilize Hindus?

01:10:51.600 --> 01:10:57.800
[Guest]: Both, because then they could also see that even post, immediately after independence,

01:10:57.800 --> 01:11:02.720
[Guest]: you see what was happening in UP, UP had agreed.

01:11:02.720 --> 01:11:06.880
[Guest]: So they could see even the ambivalence of the Congress government, so the Congress leaders

01:11:06.880 --> 01:11:07.880
[Guest]: on cows.

01:11:07.880 --> 01:11:13.000
[Guest]: Although how else was Govind Das addressing, who was Congress leader, he never left Congress

01:11:13.000 --> 01:11:22.280
[Guest]: till he was, he was, I think, till before that, he was a member of CWC.

01:11:22.280 --> 01:11:28.840
[Guest]: If you, this one, Lal Bahadur Shastri, well, Lal Bahadur Shastri didn't come out in the

01:11:28.840 --> 01:11:35.400
[Guest]: open, but Gulzari Lal Nanda quit and came in support of the movement.

01:11:35.400 --> 01:11:43.400
[Guest]: So Congress's ambivalence, they figured out, and it's also, you know, the cultural thing

01:11:43.400 --> 01:11:44.400
[Guest]: among Hindus.

01:11:44.400 --> 01:11:50.840
[Guest]: So very few people could make that distinction on cow which Nehru's Western upbringing, Nehru's

01:11:50.840 --> 01:11:56.560
[Guest]: refined man, refined thinking, he could make that distinction that don't do this, you'll

01:11:56.560 --> 01:11:58.280
[Guest]: destroy our economy.

01:11:58.280 --> 01:12:00.200
[Guest]: And he just kept it economy, nothing else.

01:12:00.200 --> 01:12:03.560
[Amit Varma]: In fact, people who talked about the cow, he called them economically illiterate.

01:12:03.560 --> 01:12:06.520
[Guest]: He was absolutely right, he made some big mistakes himself.

01:12:06.520 --> 01:12:07.520
[Guest]: But he was right about this.

01:12:07.520 --> 01:12:12.280
[Guest]: When you read that speech he gave in Parliament, when the private member bill is moved, and

01:12:12.280 --> 01:12:18.040
[Guest]: he appears in that day in Parliament, and he says, what are you two people doing?

01:12:18.040 --> 01:12:22.920
[Guest]: And so he could understand he, and he never got into this religion mumbo-jumbo, religious

01:12:22.920 --> 01:12:23.920
[Guest]: mumbo-jumbo.

01:12:23.920 --> 01:12:25.800
[Guest]: He said, let's keep it to economics.

01:12:25.800 --> 01:12:30.520
[Guest]: If you don't guys don't understand, you people talk of rural economy.

01:12:30.520 --> 01:12:34.160
[Guest]: Do you realize what this, what will do to our rural economy?

01:12:34.160 --> 01:12:42.000
[Guest]: But then, so partly it was that the right wing figured out that cow is something on

01:12:42.000 --> 01:12:46.760
[Guest]: which very few parties will have the guts to come and Nehru is gone, Nehru is dead and

01:12:46.760 --> 01:12:47.760
[Guest]: gone.

01:12:47.760 --> 01:12:53.720
[Guest]: And so Congress after Nehru, if you see, it's been a kind of, its ambivalence continues

01:12:53.720 --> 01:12:58.880
[Guest]: till now on certain issues on cow, or be it anything, even in Parliament, just to see

01:12:58.880 --> 01:13:04.120
[Guest]: on certain bills, Congress could have easily come out and kind of opposed it.

01:13:04.120 --> 01:13:08.800
[Amit Varma]: I mean, they run states where there are cow protection cells in the Parliament and so

01:13:08.800 --> 01:13:09.800
[Guest]: on.

01:13:09.800 --> 01:13:13.840
[Guest]: Yeah, look, what's happening in Madhya Pradesh or even Rajasthan instances have happened.

01:13:13.840 --> 01:13:18.640
[Guest]: So Congress has always been a lesser evil in these matters and various other things,

01:13:18.640 --> 01:13:20.720
[Guest]: of course, are the bigger evils.

01:13:20.720 --> 01:13:23.720
[Guest]: So and of course, it becomes a very easy rallying.

01:13:23.720 --> 01:13:30.040
[Guest]: It helps you paper over the large differences within the Hindu society of caste and everything.

01:13:30.040 --> 01:13:35.960
[Guest]: Cow is something on which very few people will, you know, then you only talk of cow

01:13:35.960 --> 01:13:36.960
[Guest]: for Hindus.

01:13:36.960 --> 01:13:42.720
[Guest]: You're not talking of other things like temple entry movement, every time you talk, it reveals

01:13:42.720 --> 01:13:48.160
[Guest]: the great divide in the Hindi among Hindus.

01:13:48.160 --> 01:13:49.160
[Amit Varma]: Cow doesn't.

01:13:49.160 --> 01:13:55.240
[Amit Varma]: Let's talk about caste, since you brought it up and, you know, very early on, Poddar

01:13:55.240 --> 01:13:57.800
[Amit Varma]: sort of, you know, he supports Varnashram.

01:13:57.800 --> 01:14:02.800
[Amit Varma]: And okay, so before we get to caste, there's sort of a broader question, that in terms

01:14:02.800 --> 01:14:08.360
[Amit Varma]: of their beliefs and caste, in terms of their beliefs in gender, and in both cases, beliefs

01:14:08.360 --> 01:14:11.480
[Amit Varma]: basically boil down to, you should know your place.

01:14:11.480 --> 01:14:15.600
[Amit Varma]: So within a caste system, this is a Varnashram, this is everybody's place.

01:14:15.600 --> 01:14:20.280
[Amit Varma]: If you're a woman, this is your place, and we'll discuss that in detail at some point.

01:14:20.280 --> 01:14:25.240
[Amit Varma]: And it all goes back to the whole karma thing that you are where you are, because of the

01:14:25.240 --> 01:14:27.440
[Amit Varma]: misdeeds of your past birth.

01:14:27.440 --> 01:14:29.280
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, there's no need to change it.

01:14:29.280 --> 01:14:30.960
[Guest]: This is your karma playing itself out.

01:14:30.960 --> 01:14:35.960
[Guest]: Do something well in this life and next life, maybe you will be born upper caste.

01:14:35.960 --> 01:14:43.400
[Unknown]: In the long run, we are not going to be born upper caste.

01:14:43.400 --> 01:14:45.680
[Guest]: So caste was very, very crucial to them.

01:14:45.680 --> 01:14:49.760
[Guest]: In fact, therefore, you find, right from the beginning, even early days in the first few

01:14:49.760 --> 01:14:57.040
[Guest]: issues of Kalyan also, they're talking of basically, this Chaturvarna system, the Varnashram,

01:14:57.040 --> 01:15:00.680
[Guest]: and this is what it is.

01:15:00.680 --> 01:15:07.280
[Guest]: But only after 1932, once the Poonam Pact gets signed, is when they're really agitated.

01:15:07.280 --> 01:15:12.680
[Guest]: And the first rupture in relations with Gandhi takes place, then how could you?

01:15:12.680 --> 01:15:18.200
[Guest]: And then he's kind of showing him his old articles, citing old articles of Gandhi to

01:15:18.200 --> 01:15:20.080
[Guest]: Gandhi and saying that, look what you wrote.

01:15:20.080 --> 01:15:24.800
[Guest]: But Gandhi is, the good thing about Gandhi was he was constantly evolving, admitting

01:15:24.800 --> 01:15:26.920
[Guest]: his mistakes, he's saying, yes, I did.

01:15:26.920 --> 01:15:27.920
[Guest]: So what?

01:15:27.920 --> 01:15:28.920
[Guest]: I moved on.

01:15:28.920 --> 01:15:32.920
[Guest]: This is what I think, which they could never kind of come to terms with.

01:15:32.920 --> 01:15:39.720
[Guest]: And after that, the stress on caste becomes more pronounced in Kalyan and other places.

01:15:39.720 --> 01:15:44.200
[Guest]: And they're constantly, go to the extent of saying that, you know, just because you carry,

01:15:44.200 --> 01:15:53.840
[Guest]: you know, the, this whole scavengers, because of what you do, you have germs in your body.

01:15:53.840 --> 01:15:59.420
[Guest]: Imagine saying this and getting away with it, writing it and getting away with it, kind

01:15:59.420 --> 01:16:02.720
[Guest]: of terms they use for Ambedkar.

01:16:02.720 --> 01:16:06.280
[Guest]: And because they were very worried, they were very angry with what he was doing with Hindu

01:16:06.280 --> 01:16:08.720
[Guest]: code bill, Ambedkar.

01:16:08.720 --> 01:16:13.400
[Guest]: And on top of that, second, he had married a Brahmin woman, that kind of got the code.

01:16:13.400 --> 01:16:18.080
[Amit Varma]: In your book, you've spoken about how they always called him Hinvarna, lower caste.

01:16:18.080 --> 01:16:23.200
[Guest]: Imagine addressing Hinvarna, Dr. Ambedkar, they were very, very angry with Ambedkar.

01:16:23.200 --> 01:16:29.360
[Guest]: In fact, see Nehru, they could still think he's one among us who's gone, you know, off

01:16:29.360 --> 01:16:30.360
[Guest]: track.

01:16:30.360 --> 01:16:31.360
[Guest]: But this man?

01:16:31.360 --> 01:16:32.360
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:16:32.360 --> 01:16:37.320
[Amit Varma]: And in a similar sense, something that reminded me of what even Modi does today is that when

01:16:37.320 --> 01:16:42.200
[Amit Varma]: it comes to Muslims, he'll refer to Mian Jinnah and Mian Liaqat, and you have Modi doing his

01:16:42.200 --> 01:16:44.600
[Unknown]: Mian Musharraf a decade ago.

01:16:44.600 --> 01:16:45.600
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:16:45.600 --> 01:16:50.560
[Guest]: So this is just showing them their place and constantly talking about it.

01:16:50.560 --> 01:16:55.240
[Guest]: They were so worried when he was contesting from two constituencies in Bombay, that what

01:16:55.240 --> 01:16:56.720
[Guest]: if he wins?

01:16:56.720 --> 01:17:02.520
[Guest]: And they could never forgive him for what he did to, because of the Hindu code bill.

01:17:02.520 --> 01:17:07.520
[Guest]: If he resigns, and Nehru was also not giving up on Hindu code bill, broke it, but got it

01:17:07.520 --> 01:17:08.520
[Guest]: passed.

01:17:08.520 --> 01:17:10.160
[Amit Varma]: And these guys didn't know what to do with him.

01:17:10.160 --> 01:17:12.880
[Amit Varma]: So we will come to the Hindu code bill later.

01:17:12.880 --> 01:17:17.800
[Amit Varma]: I found, you know, one of the letters from Poddar to Gandhi, you sort of reproduce was

01:17:17.800 --> 01:17:22.360
[Amit Varma]: very fascinating, where Poddar is writing to Gandhi, quote, these days a big agitation

01:17:22.360 --> 01:17:26.800
[Amit Varma]: by Dalits is going on in the country that has intensified due to your fast.

01:17:26.800 --> 01:17:31.360
[Amit Varma]: At various places, people are dining with Dalits, and they're being allowed inside temples.

01:17:31.360 --> 01:17:32.920
[Amit Varma]: Some only God knows.

01:17:32.920 --> 01:17:37.400
[Amit Varma]: Just like those believing in God and Shastras are accused of blind faith, I find that this

01:17:37.400 --> 01:17:42.400
[Amit Varma]: movement has not only become a victim of blind faith, but also there is a lack of discernment.

01:17:42.400 --> 01:17:46.000
[Amit Varma]: Even those in favor of dining with Dalits agree, though I do not equate dining with

01:17:46.000 --> 01:17:50.720
[Amit Varma]: them as a mark of equality, that they cannot be considered pure unless they have a pure

01:17:50.720 --> 01:17:55.320
[Amit Varma]: bath, wear fresh clothes, give up alcohol and meat, and at least stop feasting on dead

01:17:55.320 --> 01:17:56.320
[Amit Varma]: cattle.

01:17:56.320 --> 01:17:58.100
[Amit Varma]: Only then co-dining makes sense.

01:17:58.100 --> 01:18:02.600
[Amit Varma]: But your common dining in temple entry movement is not even checking if they fulfill those

01:18:02.600 --> 01:18:03.600
[Amit Varma]: norms.

01:18:03.600 --> 01:18:06.520
[Amit Varma]: And so on, he goes off, ranting on and on.

01:18:06.520 --> 01:18:10.640
[Amit Varma]: And in the end, he says, even Pandavas and Kauravas used to dine together, but it led

01:18:10.640 --> 01:18:11.640
[Amit Varma]: to a big battle.

01:18:11.640 --> 01:18:18.080
[Amit Varma]: And it seems as if, you know, on some of these issues, like Dalits and Muslims and cows,

01:18:18.080 --> 01:18:19.080
[Amit Varma]: he almost gets unhinged.

01:18:19.080 --> 01:18:20.080
[Guest]: Unhinged.

01:18:20.080 --> 01:18:26.120
[Guest]: And then you realize that, okay, wasn't this journal supposed to be Bhakti Gyan Vairag

01:18:26.120 --> 01:18:30.960
[Guest]: Journal, which will talk about bhakti and knowledge and renunciation.

01:18:30.960 --> 01:18:34.600
[Guest]: Look at this man, he's just, and something would happen.

01:18:34.600 --> 01:18:40.320
[Guest]: Then like one marriage, Gandhi had made this, made some announcement that he'll only attend

01:18:40.320 --> 01:18:48.280
[Guest]: marriages where at least one partner is, you know, from Dalit community, he's a Harijan.

01:18:48.280 --> 01:18:53.960
[Guest]: And this comes to Poddar's notice, he says, he's like almost abusive.

01:18:53.960 --> 01:18:56.640
[Guest]: He said he's lost his mental balance.

01:18:56.640 --> 01:19:00.480
[Guest]: But then at the same time, it's very difficult to figure out this, around the same time you

01:19:00.480 --> 01:19:07.000
[Guest]: find there's a letter, which come to him from Jamnalal Bajaj, saying that, oh, Bapu wants

01:19:07.000 --> 01:19:12.720
[Guest]: you to be part of some journal, which was bring out on again on cows or something.

01:19:12.720 --> 01:19:18.120
[Guest]: So he says, Bapu ke pyaar se mahatma ka kya lena dena, something he says, makes that distinction

01:19:18.120 --> 01:19:21.840
[Guest]: that you're a mahatma for the world, and you do all those things, which I don't approve

01:19:21.840 --> 01:19:22.840
[Guest]: of, but you're my Bapu.

01:19:22.840 --> 01:19:27.880
[Guest]: So at personal level, yeah, I relate to you, okay, fine.

01:19:27.880 --> 01:19:32.720
[Guest]: But yeah, 32 kind of gave them this, they just couldn't figure out what has happened

01:19:32.720 --> 01:19:36.160
[Guest]: to the world, you know, why people are going on and on talking about this.

01:19:36.160 --> 01:19:37.160
[Amit Varma]: That's very interesting.

01:19:37.160 --> 01:19:41.640
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the whole this is almost I mean, forgive me if that sounds kind of sacrilegious, but

01:19:41.640 --> 01:19:46.440
[Amit Varma]: this whole journey of Gandhi on caste also is kind of funny, where it seems to me that

01:19:46.440 --> 01:19:50.440
[Amit Varma]: okay, at one point, he talks about Varnashram and how the caste have their place and basically

01:19:50.440 --> 01:19:54.360
[Amit Varma]: says the same kind of thing Poddar would have utterly agreed with.

01:19:54.360 --> 01:19:57.720
[Amit Varma]: And then he goes to this other side, where he says that no, no, we need to dine together

01:19:57.720 --> 01:19:59.360
[Amit Varma]: and all of that.

01:19:59.360 --> 01:20:05.520
[Amit Varma]: But to me, it seems like if you go by some of his actions, he's still posturing a bit

01:20:05.520 --> 01:20:08.320
[Amit Varma]: and Ambedkar kind of sees through it and the Ambedkar Gandhi debates are...

01:20:08.320 --> 01:20:13.320
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah, therefore they never, Ambedkar, see, even the pact was a bit of a compromise

01:20:13.320 --> 01:20:16.960
[Guest]: and Ambedkar is always suspicious of him throughout.

01:20:16.960 --> 01:20:23.080
[Guest]: It's not that the relationship ever is very, very, you know, the kind of relations that

01:20:23.080 --> 01:20:28.640
[Guest]: Gandhi had with Nehru or something, no, he and they were all with it, they inhabited

01:20:28.640 --> 01:20:29.640
[Guest]: different universes.

01:20:29.640 --> 01:20:34.280
[Guest]: It was a very, very momentary thing what happened in the Puri Pact and all that.

01:20:34.280 --> 01:20:35.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:20:35.280 --> 01:20:40.520
[Amit Varma]: And so Gandhi was, in a sense, it almost feels like Needa Ghar Ka Na Ghat Ka, that he's lost

01:20:40.520 --> 01:20:44.760
[Amit Varma]: the Sangeeta Press and he's lost Ambedkar and he's basically in all his posturing in

01:20:44.760 --> 01:20:45.760
[Guest]: the games.

01:20:45.760 --> 01:20:52.480
[Guest]: Gandhi always had enough to move on, Gandhi didn't care much about these small things

01:20:52.480 --> 01:20:57.040
[Amit Varma]: of what Poddar thought or what Ambedkar was doing.

01:20:57.040 --> 01:21:02.200
[Amit Varma]: And the most fascinating parts of your book are parts which actually deal with gender.

01:21:02.200 --> 01:21:06.000
[Amit Varma]: And the remarkable thing is how you point out that even till today, they have those

01:21:06.000 --> 01:21:11.560
[Amit Varma]: same kind of incredibly regressive views.

01:21:11.560 --> 01:21:14.480
[Amit Varma]: And I'm just going to quote a bit.

01:21:14.480 --> 01:21:21.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, their fundamental sort of belief is again, quoting from your book, quote, independence

01:21:21.360 --> 01:21:25.440
[Amit Varma]: is not promised to women in the Hindu social structure, a woman has to live with a father

01:21:25.440 --> 01:21:29.560
[Amit Varma]: till marriage, with a husband as a married woman, and after his demise, she has to live

01:21:29.560 --> 01:21:32.520
[Amit Varma]: either with a son or some other relative.

01:21:32.520 --> 01:21:35.240
[Amit Varma]: She cannot be independent at any cost.

01:21:35.240 --> 01:21:42.760
[Amit Varma]: And a little later while talking about menstruation, Poddar writes, I'll quote from your book again,

01:21:42.760 --> 01:21:47.160
[Amit Varma]: presenting a skewed understanding of female sexuality, Poddar wrote that during her menstrual

01:21:47.160 --> 01:21:50.840
[Amit Varma]: period, a woman had an uncontrollable urge for sex.

01:21:50.840 --> 01:21:55.760
[Amit Varma]: And to channelize this vasana, there is a system of vasana, a sexual urge, there is

01:21:55.760 --> 01:21:58.920
[Amit Varma]: a system of marrying girls by the time they attain puberty.

01:21:58.920 --> 01:22:02.840
[Amit Varma]: In the husband's shelter, a woman's sexual desire does not reach others and she is safe

01:22:02.840 --> 01:22:04.240
[Amit Varma]: from getting polluted.

01:22:04.240 --> 01:22:09.280
[Amit Varma]: If she is not married, her sexual desire degenerates into debauchery, just the way it is happening

01:22:09.280 --> 01:22:10.280
[Amit Varma]: in Europe.

01:22:10.280 --> 01:22:12.840
[Amit Varma]: The core job of a woman was to serve the world.

01:22:12.840 --> 01:22:13.840
[Amit Varma]: How?

01:22:13.840 --> 01:22:20.000
[Amit Varma]: Poddar used two terms, utpadan, which means manufacturing or production, and nirman, which

01:22:20.000 --> 01:22:21.720
[Amit Varma]: means construction or creation.

01:22:21.720 --> 01:22:28.440
[Amit Varma]: Thus, a woman's job was to procreate and nurture quality men, stop quote.

01:22:28.440 --> 01:22:37.680
[Guest]: You know, when I was actually writing this part, my niece was, my daughter was very small,

01:22:37.680 --> 01:22:41.480
[Guest]: she was in I think, she was still in class seventh or something.

01:22:41.480 --> 01:22:42.480
[Guest]: So I made her read it.

01:22:42.480 --> 01:22:43.840
[Guest]: I said, What do you think of this?

01:22:43.840 --> 01:22:48.160
[Guest]: I made them read that pamphlet as what do you think of it?

01:22:48.160 --> 01:22:54.160
[Guest]: I made my niece who's elder and who's in engineering college, so I better read it.

01:22:54.160 --> 01:22:55.960
[Guest]: Is this what you're writing?

01:22:55.960 --> 01:22:59.600
[Guest]: So they were not very sure what what I have to do with that.

01:22:59.600 --> 01:23:03.360
[Guest]: So I said, Well, this is what it is and still being sold.

01:23:03.360 --> 01:23:08.520
[Guest]: See, Isthri Dharam Prasanthi, the last one when the my Hindi translation was being done

01:23:08.520 --> 01:23:13.120
[Guest]: and I lost my own copy, I picked it up from railway, I had gone to drop some on the railway

01:23:13.120 --> 01:23:14.800
[Guest]: streets and I got it.

01:23:14.800 --> 01:23:23.680
[Guest]: And just look at the circulation, it's something produced in 1926, getting sold in 2019, has

01:23:23.680 --> 01:23:30.280
[Guest]: a constituency, has a readership, selling more than Chetan Bhagat, then what is happening?

01:23:30.280 --> 01:23:34.400
[Guest]: Someone somewhere is reading it, and even 10%, I don't know what percentage, I have

01:23:34.400 --> 01:23:38.320
[Guest]: no figures, but someone is getting influenced too.

01:23:38.320 --> 01:23:44.080
[Guest]: So what is happening when you see this strange kind of things happening outside the urban

01:23:44.080 --> 01:23:49.160
[Guest]: spaces, you realize that people are getting influenced what is being done to women in

01:23:49.160 --> 01:23:54.680
[Guest]: terms of just controlling their sexuality, basically control, you know, using whatever

01:23:54.680 --> 01:23:56.080
[Guest]: be the absurd logic.

01:23:56.080 --> 01:23:57.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:23:57.080 --> 01:24:00.400
[Amit Varma]: Basically, the whole deal is that a woman's only job is to make her husband look good

01:24:00.400 --> 01:24:01.400
[Amit Varma]: to the world and to serve him.

01:24:01.400 --> 01:24:08.160
[Guest]: You inhabit the inner space, the four walls of the house, and just procreate.

01:24:08.160 --> 01:24:09.160
[Guest]: That's it.

01:24:09.160 --> 01:24:11.040
[Amit Varma]: You have no other job.

01:24:11.040 --> 01:24:14.520
[Amit Varma]: And you know, in this context, one of the things I noticed in your book, though you

01:24:14.520 --> 01:24:19.360
[Amit Varma]: don't always call it out as such, but it's, is that what Kalyan is also doing, what Padar

01:24:19.360 --> 01:24:22.040
[Amit Varma]: is doing is a lot of what today we would call fake news.

01:24:22.040 --> 01:24:28.600
[Amit Varma]: They are just randomly and I found a few examples of these, and like in one place, you say,

01:24:28.600 --> 01:24:33.040
[Amit Varma]: quote, Padar cited a Labour MP speech in the British Parliament in which he reportedly

01:24:33.040 --> 01:24:36.960
[Amit Varma]: said 40% of girls under 20 got pregnant before marriage.

01:24:36.960 --> 01:24:42.040
[Amit Varma]: And among married women, the first child was illegitimate in 25% of the cases, which is

01:24:42.040 --> 01:24:43.040
[Unknown]: complete rubbish.

01:24:43.040 --> 01:24:51.040
[Amit Varma]: And there was a similar thing from Lahore about how all the girls over 12 are pregnant.

01:24:51.040 --> 01:24:57.880
[Amit Varma]: You know, and one that is not, and okay, but another one, Padar claimed without substantiation

01:24:57.880 --> 01:25:03.080
[Amit Varma]: that sexually transmitted diseases were prevalent among 50% of students.

01:25:03.080 --> 01:25:07.960
[Amit Varma]: And another one, which is not related to gender, but I found it so funny was, quote, one of

01:25:07.960 --> 01:25:12.800
[Amit Varma]: Gandhi's associates telling people in Gujarat that cow fat was mixed in the manufacture

01:25:12.800 --> 01:25:18.640
[Amit Varma]: of foreign cloth, or a leaflet stating that 1000 pounds of coloured Manchester cloth consisted

01:25:18.640 --> 01:25:21.680
[Amit Varma]: of 300 pounds of cow and big blood, stop quote.

01:25:21.680 --> 01:25:23.480
[Guest]: This is how they propagate it.

01:25:23.480 --> 01:25:28.020
[Guest]: No, no substantiation, nobody will ask, someone will print it.

01:25:28.020 --> 01:25:33.760
[Guest]: So we are now worried about fake news from social media, which is still your print is

01:25:33.760 --> 01:25:38.160
[Guest]: still more or less still all right, you know.

01:25:38.160 --> 01:25:42.240
[Amit Varma]: And then it was happening in print, you know, and it was everyone was doing the most popular

01:25:42.240 --> 01:25:44.800
[Amit Varma]: Heartland magazine, reaching everyone.

01:25:44.800 --> 01:25:50.360
[Guest]: And you don't have any Pratik Sinha or Alt News to sort of pass this.

01:25:50.360 --> 01:25:55.280
[Guest]: So you randomly are saying Labour MP, who is this Labour MP, then they will quote some

01:25:55.280 --> 01:26:00.840
[Guest]: study about something happened to the generation of women, who, what study, which study, they

01:26:00.840 --> 01:26:02.800
[Amit Varma]: will never mention it.

01:26:02.800 --> 01:26:07.680
[Amit Varma]: And there's other stuff like, for example, at a later point, he's in the 1948 Nariyang

01:26:07.680 --> 01:26:15.760
[Amit Varma]: Poddar, sort of glorifies Sati, and his narrative rests on his genuine scientific belief.

01:26:15.760 --> 01:26:20.760
[Amit Varma]: When you put scientific in good words, of course, that fire can emanate from a distraught

01:26:20.760 --> 01:26:22.720
[Amit Varma]: widow's shoulder and heart.

01:26:22.720 --> 01:26:24.960
[Amit Varma]: So he's saying no one sets a woman on fire.

01:26:24.960 --> 01:26:30.560
[Amit Varma]: But if she is pativrata and a virtuous woman, her sorrow for her husband will make her spontaneously

01:26:30.560 --> 01:26:34.400
[Amit Varma]: combust, which she calls scientific.

01:26:34.400 --> 01:26:37.160
[Guest]: And this stuff is just nuts and millions of people are reading it.

01:26:37.160 --> 01:26:43.320
[Guest]: Reading it, mind you, Nariyang is still in circulation, Nariyang is very much, it keeps

01:26:43.320 --> 01:26:44.320
[Guest]: getting reprinted.

01:26:44.320 --> 01:26:47.560
[Guest]: And Nariyang is one of these year end specials, 700 pages.

01:26:47.560 --> 01:26:50.920
[Guest]: At the beginning of the year, they have special, which is like 1000 page special.

01:26:50.920 --> 01:26:51.920
[Guest]: You have all these?

01:26:51.920 --> 01:26:52.920
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah, I have.

01:26:52.920 --> 01:26:53.920
[Guest]: All of these?

01:26:53.920 --> 01:26:54.920
[Guest]: Yeah, I have kept all of it.

01:26:54.920 --> 01:26:57.920
[Guest]: I should have asked you to bring one.

01:26:57.920 --> 01:27:02.400
[Guest]: Yeah, I have all of Nariyang, Hinduang, everything.

01:27:02.400 --> 01:27:03.460
[Amit Varma]: Have all the issues.

01:27:03.460 --> 01:27:05.360
[Amit Varma]: And what is the noise to signal ratio?

01:27:05.360 --> 01:27:09.560
[Amit Varma]: Like how much of this is this bullshit kind of fake news nonsense and how much is actually

01:27:09.560 --> 01:27:10.560
[Guest]: well reasoned stuff?

01:27:10.560 --> 01:27:17.000
[Guest]: See, when it comes to women, I'll say 100% is bullshit, of course.

01:27:17.000 --> 01:27:19.960
[Guest]: On cow, they were doing both the things.

01:27:19.960 --> 01:27:25.640
[Guest]: See, Gosevang comes at a time, for instance, when the movement is at its slowest step.

01:27:25.640 --> 01:27:32.160
[Guest]: So it's talking, it is very economic in nature, this is 90s, 93 or something, if I'm getting

01:27:32.160 --> 01:27:33.940
[Guest]: the year right.

01:27:33.940 --> 01:27:40.400
[Guest]: So by then, the movement was not there, you know, Ram temple movement was at the center

01:27:40.400 --> 01:27:41.400
[Guest]: stage.

01:27:41.400 --> 01:27:47.480
[Guest]: It has some things, it has a few articles by experts, which is talking of how to make

01:27:47.480 --> 01:27:51.080
[Guest]: economic use of cow, which is fine.

01:27:51.080 --> 01:27:54.640
[Guest]: You can even sense the change of narrative.

01:27:54.640 --> 01:27:56.480
[Guest]: Then it's not a strident.

01:27:56.480 --> 01:27:58.920
[Amit Varma]: They're trying to make it sound respectable.

01:27:58.920 --> 01:28:05.280
[Guest]: So they made that distinction of Govang, which had already come in the mean Gosevang, where

01:28:05.280 --> 01:28:10.280
[Guest]: was the, they were discussing economics of it and various other aspects.

01:28:10.280 --> 01:28:17.960
[Guest]: Otherwise, see, they will always throw this Shastras or some Sutras or some slokas or

01:28:17.960 --> 01:28:22.520
[Guest]: something, which ordinary reader, I don't know how many of them would understand.

01:28:22.520 --> 01:28:27.040
[Guest]: I'm not saying because I myself never cross checked when it came to the religious texts.

01:28:27.040 --> 01:28:29.440
[Guest]: So I'm not in a position to comment on that.

01:28:29.440 --> 01:28:37.040
[Guest]: But yes, when you claim the scientific study on women or Sati or women burning on their

01:28:37.040 --> 01:28:42.120
[Unknown]: own because of some combustion happening inside, it's like, what do you do to that?

01:28:42.120 --> 01:28:45.920
[Unknown]: You know, you write, you read, it freaks you out, you know, what do you do with this such

01:28:45.920 --> 01:28:46.920
[Amit Varma]: thing, you know?

01:28:46.920 --> 01:28:47.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:28:47.920 --> 01:28:52.080
[Amit Varma]: And for example, I mean, a lot of their stands to do with gender are crazy, like they were

01:28:52.080 --> 01:28:53.360
[Amit Varma]: against birth control.

01:28:53.360 --> 01:28:58.360
[Amit Varma]: So again, quoting from your book, quote Poddar saying, encouraging artificial methods is

01:28:58.360 --> 01:29:01.280
[Amit Varma]: like encouraging evil artificial methods of birth control.

01:29:01.280 --> 01:29:03.680
[Amit Varma]: It makes men and women frivolous.

01:29:03.680 --> 01:29:07.560
[Amit Varma]: Artificial methods would result in impotence and decline in sperm count.

01:29:07.560 --> 01:29:10.240
[Amit Varma]: This remedy would prove to be worse than the disease.

01:29:10.240 --> 01:29:15.640
[Amit Varma]: Elsewhere, he's ranting against cinema and he says, quote, first and foremost, female

01:29:15.640 --> 01:29:17.720
[Amit Varma]: actors should be thrown out completely.

01:29:17.720 --> 01:29:20.560
[Amit Varma]: They are the root cause of all evil.

01:29:20.560 --> 01:29:23.440
[Amit Varma]: And film should not consist of anything that perverts a mind.

01:29:23.440 --> 01:29:27.560
[Amit Varma]: There will be hangama at first, but then people will get used to the changes.

01:29:27.560 --> 01:29:28.560
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

01:29:28.560 --> 01:29:33.160
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting that while all this is happening, what Poddar has done and probably

01:29:33.160 --> 01:29:38.160
[Amit Varma]: shows his genius as an editor, and you alluded to it earlier, is that he has an extremely

01:29:38.160 --> 01:29:44.720
[Amit Varma]: wide cast of contributors to, you know, it's not just a typical Hindu nationalist in the

01:29:44.720 --> 01:29:45.720
[Guest]: Hindu community.

01:29:45.720 --> 01:29:46.720
[Guest]: No, no, no, no.

01:29:46.720 --> 01:29:47.720
[Guest]: You're very, very smart that way.

01:29:47.720 --> 01:29:51.200
[Guest]: You know, you have people like Radhakrishnan writing for some issues, Radhakrishnan was

01:29:51.200 --> 01:29:55.800
[Guest]: not writing on controversial, he was a philosopher, he kept to that, he didn't get into areas

01:29:55.800 --> 01:29:56.800
[Guest]: which he was not.

01:29:56.800 --> 01:29:57.800
[Guest]: Gandhi wrote a lot.

01:29:57.800 --> 01:29:58.800
[Guest]: Gandhi wrote a lot.

01:29:58.800 --> 01:30:06.440
[Guest]: Nehru is the only one which, even he got the big Hindi writers to write, you know, Premchand

01:30:06.440 --> 01:30:11.360
[Guest]: to Nirala to everyone, and they'll privately say what to do, we don't know anything.

01:30:11.360 --> 01:30:19.120
[Guest]: But because of his aura, his charm, whatever it is, even Premchand wrote, Nirala wrote.

01:30:19.120 --> 01:30:24.360
[Guest]: I think among that generation of Hindi writers, Mathilisaran Gupt was the only one who wrote

01:30:24.360 --> 01:30:30.880
[Guest]: enthusiastically, Hariod maybe, but others were not very keen, someone like Nirala was

01:30:30.880 --> 01:30:32.680
[Guest]: too irreverent to get into this.

01:30:32.680 --> 01:30:33.680
[Amit Varma]: But then well,

01:30:33.680 --> 01:30:38.480
[Amit Varma]: And it's almost like Poddar has like strategically decided that, okay, what do I do to make it

01:30:38.480 --> 01:30:43.280
[Amit Varma]: as respectable in this way as possible, one, get all the politicians, two, get all the

01:30:43.280 --> 01:30:48.240
[Amit Varma]: Hindi literators, three, get people from other religions, other religions also, and four,

01:30:48.240 --> 01:30:49.880
[Guest]: get people from abroad.

01:30:49.880 --> 01:30:56.160
[Guest]: So it gained them a lot of respect because of that, you know, and it helped build a huge

01:30:56.160 --> 01:30:57.160
[Guest]: network.

01:30:57.160 --> 01:30:59.080
[Amit Varma]: And let's move on now to the next theme.

01:30:59.080 --> 01:31:03.720
[Amit Varma]: And this is not really a theme as just an underlying backdrop to all of this, which

01:31:03.720 --> 01:31:06.200
[Amit Varma]: is their attitudes towards Muslims.

01:31:06.200 --> 01:31:11.280
[Amit Varma]: I mean, even if they had a few Muslim writers, there's a lot of this constant baiting when

01:31:11.280 --> 01:31:14.960
[Amit Varma]: Jinnah is mentioned as Mian Jinnah, when Liaqat is mentioned.

01:31:14.960 --> 01:31:19.800
[Amit Varma]: And in part of the narrative of Sanatan Dharm as this pure religion that has existed from

01:31:19.800 --> 01:31:23.960
[Amit Varma]: time immemorial is also a specific narrative they're building up of Muslims.

01:31:23.960 --> 01:31:27.720
[Amit Varma]: For example, again, quoting from your book, you write, integral to the narrative was a

01:31:27.720 --> 01:31:33.800
[Amit Varma]: depiction of Muslim men as the other, libidinous, sexually dissipated and voluptuously lustful,

01:31:33.800 --> 01:31:37.880
[Amit Varma]: from whom Hindu women had to be protected at all costs.

01:31:37.880 --> 01:31:41.760
[Amit Varma]: And later you write how the Hindu nationalist organization like Gita Press called on Hindu

01:31:41.760 --> 01:31:46.800
[Amit Varma]: women, not only to avoid lag bangles, which you know, those guys made, but also not to

01:31:46.800 --> 01:31:51.800
[Amit Varma]: board horse carts written driven by Muslims, not to keep Muslim servants, not to invite

01:31:51.800 --> 01:31:58.120
[Amit Varma]: Muslims prostitutes or singers and joyous occasion not to buy household items from Muslims and

01:31:58.120 --> 01:31:59.120
[Amit Varma]: so on and so forth.

01:31:59.120 --> 01:32:04.520
[Amit Varma]: And so it's not just a cultural narrative of the saving your women from the lustful

01:32:04.520 --> 01:32:05.760
[Amit Varma]: Muslim male.

01:32:05.760 --> 01:32:09.680
[Amit Varma]: But there's also the economic purpose of cutting off patronage from Muslims.

01:32:09.680 --> 01:32:13.080
[Guest]: So you find actually a lot for is happening.

01:32:13.080 --> 01:32:18.400
[Guest]: You see the roots there, you know, during even on Hindu code bill, maybe we'll discuss

01:32:18.400 --> 01:32:19.400
[Guest]: it later.

01:32:19.400 --> 01:32:25.880
[Guest]: But you find that similar thing was happening as far as the love jihad and all similar arguments

01:32:25.880 --> 01:32:26.880
[Guest]: were happening.

01:32:26.880 --> 01:32:35.160
[Guest]: And so Muslims kept coming to their narrative one way or the other.

01:32:35.160 --> 01:32:41.080
[Guest]: When they discuss cow, Muslims come, when they discuss women, Muslims come, you know,

01:32:41.080 --> 01:32:45.800
[Guest]: you protect your cows from the Muslims because they consume, you protect your Hindu women

01:32:45.800 --> 01:32:48.000
[Guest]: because Muslim men are limited.

01:32:48.000 --> 01:32:52.400
[Guest]: In fact, it's considered a compliment if a woman is like a cow.

01:32:52.400 --> 01:32:57.720
[Guest]: And it also there is a deep seated inferiority complex vis-a-vis Muslim men, you find them

01:32:57.720 --> 01:33:00.760
[Guest]: that there is something about Muslim men.

01:33:00.760 --> 01:33:03.040
[Guest]: Why are Hindu women attracted?

01:33:03.040 --> 01:33:09.760
[Guest]: And this I found not only in Kalyan, but even in some of the contemporary journals, for

01:33:09.760 --> 01:33:14.520
[Guest]: instance, there was this journal, pretty popular called Hindu Punch.

01:33:14.520 --> 01:33:19.440
[Guest]: I have some issues of that journal and you will find that this is they're constantly

01:33:19.440 --> 01:33:24.040
[Guest]: talking about there's something wrong about us, about our women.

01:33:24.040 --> 01:33:25.800
[Guest]: Why are they so attracted to Muslim men?

01:33:25.800 --> 01:33:29.160
[Guest]: And they're going to do very graphic reasons, which one may not talk about.

01:33:29.160 --> 01:33:34.120
[Guest]: But so it comes from a deep inferiority complex.

01:33:34.120 --> 01:33:36.800
[Amit Varma]: Where do you think this insecurity comes from?

01:33:36.800 --> 01:33:41.160
[Amit Varma]: Like, is it just a historical narrative of oh, they invaded us and raped our women and

01:33:41.160 --> 01:33:42.160
[Amit Varma]: all of that?

01:33:42.160 --> 01:33:46.720
[Amit Varma]: Or is it also something contemporary where they find that Muslim men are just more virile

01:33:46.720 --> 01:33:48.480
[Guest]: and they're dominating?

01:33:48.480 --> 01:33:55.840
[Guest]: That's the narrative of if you ask any pracharak privately, he'll tell you this virile thing

01:33:55.840 --> 01:34:00.120
[Guest]: that you know, they're more viriles, therefore, they need four wives.

01:34:00.120 --> 01:34:07.000
[Guest]: So they build their own world, even if you ask them how many Muslim men they know, in

01:34:07.000 --> 01:34:11.560
[Guest]: these times, were four wives, forget four, even two wives, they don't have any name,

01:34:11.560 --> 01:34:12.560
[Guest]: you know.

01:34:12.560 --> 01:34:18.760
[Guest]: So this is how they build and the interesting part is that, how this narrative is still

01:34:18.760 --> 01:34:23.720
[Guest]: alive today is not only alive, it's doing very well, actually, and especially in the

01:34:23.720 --> 01:34:26.120
[Guest]: last six years now, more than five years.

01:34:26.120 --> 01:34:27.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:34:27.120 --> 01:34:30.840
[Amit Varma]: And one wonders whether there is any logical end to this, or it's just a really great way

01:34:30.840 --> 01:34:40.320
[Amit Varma]: to sort of mobilize the troops, so to say, let's kind of now talk about the Gita Press's

01:34:40.320 --> 01:34:45.400
[Amit Varma]: rising involvement in politics from the 40 onwards, because as you pointed out, when

01:34:45.400 --> 01:34:48.560
[Amit Varma]: they started, it was like a cultural thing.

01:34:48.560 --> 01:34:53.200
[Amit Varma]: They didn't really get involved in politics, even though Poddar was close to a lot of politicians,

01:34:53.200 --> 01:34:57.440
[Amit Varma]: but they didn't really get involved in this, certainly they were never against the British

01:34:57.440 --> 01:34:58.960
[Amit Varma]: in any way.

01:34:58.960 --> 01:35:05.960
[Amit Varma]: But there were a number of sort of hot buttons which came up as the 40s came on, and one

01:35:05.960 --> 01:35:08.640
[Amit Varma]: as independence approach was partition.

01:35:08.640 --> 01:35:09.640
[Guest]: Tell me a bit about that.

01:35:09.640 --> 01:35:14.800
[Guest]: Partition, see, partition, just like, as I told you, during the 30s, when the caste thing

01:35:14.800 --> 01:35:23.400
[Guest]: came about, they turned, they forgot what the journal was meant to do, 40s, it became

01:35:23.400 --> 01:35:24.400
[Guest]: more so.

01:35:24.400 --> 01:35:31.360
[Guest]: 40s, in fact, so much so that in 46, one of their issue, which was called Malviyank, had

01:35:31.360 --> 01:35:34.200
[Guest]: to be banned by the United Provinces government.

01:35:34.200 --> 01:35:36.920
[Guest]: It was so communal, it was so communal.

01:35:36.920 --> 01:35:43.280
[Guest]: It also had the last interview, given by Madan Mohan Malviya, he died in November.

01:35:43.280 --> 01:35:46.200
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I believe this is the first time they did a special issue.

01:35:46.200 --> 01:35:50.920
[Guest]: They did a special issue for anyone, they never did it for anyone in that they have

01:35:50.920 --> 01:35:52.880
[Amit Varma]: not done it till now on anyone.

01:35:52.880 --> 01:35:55.440
[Amit Varma]: I mean, when Poddar died, they did a special issue, no?

01:35:55.440 --> 01:35:57.840
[Guest]: I don't think so.

01:35:57.840 --> 01:35:58.840
[Amit Varma]: I must be mistaken.

01:35:58.840 --> 01:35:59.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:35:59.840 --> 01:36:00.840
[Guest]: No, I don't think so.

01:36:00.840 --> 01:36:02.840
[Guest]: I didn't come across any.

01:36:02.840 --> 01:36:11.440
[Guest]: So, and then it was so communal and, you know, from, and what it was doing was, it was getting

01:36:11.440 --> 01:36:16.720
[Guest]: information from all the newspapers, their kind of newspapers, you know, many newspapers,

01:36:16.720 --> 01:36:21.480
[Guest]: which they thought was kind of furthering the Hindu cause.

01:36:21.480 --> 01:36:25.480
[Guest]: And they were talking only of violence and they were very selective in news.

01:36:25.480 --> 01:36:29.880
[Guest]: In fact, at one point, Poddar says, some of my friends are saying that, how come you're

01:36:29.880 --> 01:36:32.920
[Guest]: only writing about Muslims killing Hindus?

01:36:32.920 --> 01:36:33.920
[Guest]: Okay.

01:36:33.920 --> 01:36:39.120
[Guest]: So Hindus also killing Muslims, he admits very grudgingly.

01:36:39.120 --> 01:36:48.280
[Guest]: The entire period, if you see from 44 onwards till almost 47, they're very, very upset.

01:36:48.280 --> 01:36:54.440
[Guest]: They're trying to, especially once they realize that Pakistan is a reality now, there's no

01:36:54.440 --> 01:36:57.400
[Guest]: going back, then they become even more so.

01:36:57.400 --> 01:37:01.400
[Guest]: Now they have added grouse that, well, you listen to Muslims, you've given them.

01:37:01.400 --> 01:37:04.800
[Guest]: So now is the time for us to turn, to become a Hindu Rashtra.

01:37:04.800 --> 01:37:05.800
[Guest]: Okay.

01:37:05.800 --> 01:37:06.800
[Guest]: Muslims are gone.

01:37:06.800 --> 01:37:07.800
[Guest]: Good.

01:37:07.800 --> 01:37:10.320
[Guest]: Now we become a Hindu Rashtra.

01:37:10.320 --> 01:37:15.040
[Guest]: And then they find the Constituent Assembly, this gentleman Nehru is discussing Hindu code

01:37:15.040 --> 01:37:17.760
[Guest]: bill, which freaks them out.

01:37:17.760 --> 01:37:27.560
[Guest]: And that entire period, 44, 45 to 47, till Gandhi's assassination or before Gandhi's

01:37:27.560 --> 01:37:34.960
[Guest]: assassination, the entire Kalyan becomes a rabidly common, issue after issue on everything,

01:37:34.960 --> 01:37:41.920
[Guest]: you know, they ran this one, Bidacharan Shukla's father, who was a member of the Constituent

01:37:41.920 --> 01:37:47.760
[Guest]: Assembly, and again, party, again, on the side, he was among those right wing element

01:37:47.760 --> 01:37:48.760
[Guest]: within Congress.

01:37:48.760 --> 01:37:55.560
[Guest]: He wrote a multi, he wrote a serial, four part series, or three part series on what

01:37:55.560 --> 01:38:00.440
[Guest]: should happen to Hindi, you know, and very, very particular about how it should not get

01:38:00.440 --> 01:38:07.420
[Guest]: polluted, how those should be done away with, it was a long and four part series, imagine.

01:38:07.420 --> 01:38:12.880
[Guest]: So they were kind of bothered about everything, so what should happen post 47, now it has

01:38:12.880 --> 01:38:13.880
[Guest]: happened.

01:38:13.880 --> 01:38:19.080
[Guest]: But on the violence itself, and then there's this famous, which I call a fake news in what

01:38:19.080 --> 01:38:25.040
[Guest]: this Bengali woman, this pamphlet, which they produce all over, which gets noted in Bombay,

01:38:25.040 --> 01:38:32.280
[Guest]: we noticed in Bombay, Allahabad, Gorakhpur, and frankly, who is this woman, nobody knows.

01:38:32.280 --> 01:38:38.760
[Guest]: And Kalyan, because of its circulation, it was reaching ordinary Hindu homes, it was,

01:38:38.760 --> 01:38:45.280
[Guest]: and in a way, it became for RSS and various other organizations, it was a very easy vehicle

01:38:45.280 --> 01:38:48.080
[Guest]: to get their point across.

01:38:48.080 --> 01:38:55.360
[Guest]: In fact, entire 1946 Gorakhpur session of Hindu Mahasabha, the resolutions that they

01:38:55.360 --> 01:39:00.600
[Guest]: pass, you find Kalyan reproducing it in a different form, as a set of demands that they

01:39:00.600 --> 01:39:07.760
[Guest]: had from the now, New India, which was minus the Muslims, because the Pakistan had come

01:39:07.760 --> 01:39:13.560
[Guest]: up, which is like even now you find that those same things, someone or the other is talking

01:39:13.560 --> 01:39:16.200
[Guest]: about, especially since 2014.

01:39:16.200 --> 01:39:19.720
[Amit Varma]: And what kind of struck me was like, on the one hand, they're very frustrated, because

01:39:19.720 --> 01:39:23.000
[Amit Varma]: they're like the Muslims got their Pakistan, but where is our Hindu Rashtra, I think they

01:39:23.000 --> 01:39:28.160
[Amit Varma]: use the term Khichri for what they were left with, and I love Khichri, I think it's great.

01:39:28.160 --> 01:39:32.520
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, there's almost in some places, I sensed a little bit of glee that

01:39:32.520 --> 01:39:34.960
[Amit Varma]: this is an opportunity for them to push their agenda.

01:39:34.960 --> 01:39:40.000
[Amit Varma]: For example, quoting from your book about Noah Khali, you say, quote, the Hindu Mahasabha,

01:39:40.000 --> 01:39:44.360
[Amit Varma]: which had dispatched senior leaders like Ashutosh Lahiri, Shama Prasad Mukherjee, NC Chatterjee

01:39:44.360 --> 01:39:49.080
[Amit Varma]: and Pandit Narendra Nath Das to Noah Khali for relief work, did not fail to see the long

01:39:49.080 --> 01:39:51.080
[Amit Varma]: term gain for the community.

01:39:51.080 --> 01:39:55.200
[Amit Varma]: And now you quote within that, notwithstanding this great catastrophe, it is a matter of

01:39:55.200 --> 01:40:00.440
[Amit Varma]: satisfaction to the members of the relief committee, to see a keen sense of fellow feeling

01:40:00.440 --> 01:40:05.040
[Amit Varma]: now awakened amongst all Hindus in every province of India, stop quote.

01:40:05.040 --> 01:40:07.720
[Amit Varma]: So people are being slaughtered on both sides.

01:40:07.720 --> 01:40:12.520
[Amit Varma]: And they see it as an opportunity to continue with the polarization.

01:40:12.520 --> 01:40:18.760
[Guest]: See had Gandhi not been assassinated in 48, these guys would have been in power much,

01:40:18.760 --> 01:40:25.000
[Guest]: much earlier, maybe not in 51, 52, they would have come to power, maybe by 57.

01:40:25.000 --> 01:40:27.400
[Guest]: But max 62 election.

01:40:27.400 --> 01:40:28.400
[Guest]: Really?

01:40:28.400 --> 01:40:29.400
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:40:29.400 --> 01:40:34.240
[Guest]: This Gandhi assassination kept them, it was set back for 20 years.

01:40:34.240 --> 01:40:39.760
[Guest]: So you find them coming back to, you know, making noise only in the 60s.

01:40:39.760 --> 01:40:45.320
[Guest]: Sometime, you know, 65 election, Jan Sangh, otherwise, they were in the, they were there,

01:40:45.320 --> 01:40:49.360
[Guest]: of course, there was a strong perimeter, Jan Sangh was very much there.

01:40:49.360 --> 01:40:52.200
[Guest]: But they never posed challenge.

01:40:52.200 --> 01:40:57.800
[Guest]: And the generation of people, they just couldn't come to terms with this assassination.

01:40:57.800 --> 01:40:59.760
[Guest]: They wouldn't have won 47.

01:40:59.760 --> 01:41:05.440
[Guest]: If Gandhi was not assassinated, these guys would have come much earlier.

01:41:05.440 --> 01:41:11.200
[Amit Varma]: And that also brings me to the question of that, is our nation's destiny then from that

01:41:11.200 --> 01:41:16.640
[Amit Varma]: time, the way things have unveiled and unraveled, purely a question of happenstance and dumb

01:41:16.640 --> 01:41:21.160
[Amit Varma]: luck, whether good luck or bad luck is depends on how you look at it, that there was absolutely

01:41:21.160 --> 01:41:25.000
[Amit Varma]: just one guy who was against this tide, and that was Nehru, and he is a guy who happened

01:41:25.000 --> 01:41:29.400
[Amit Varma]: to be Prime Minister, who happened to outlive all these other guys like your Patels and

01:41:29.400 --> 01:41:30.400
[Amit Varma]: whatever.

01:41:30.400 --> 01:41:35.040
[Guest]: Nehru and the whole lot, whole generation, I'll not say Nehru alone, because the whole

01:41:35.040 --> 01:41:40.360
[Guest]: generation of people, even a lot of his colleagues, a lot of his partymen.

01:41:40.360 --> 01:41:45.320
[Amit Varma]: But the other dominant political figures like Patel, like Panth, like Rajendra Prasad, were

01:41:45.320 --> 01:41:46.320
[Guest]: also...

01:41:46.320 --> 01:41:52.040
[Guest]: They were, but still, the larger, the new India, the fervor of new India, which he wanted

01:41:52.040 --> 01:41:53.520
[Guest]: to build was very much in there.

01:41:53.520 --> 01:41:56.840
[Guest]: There were a lot of people who subscribe to that belief.

01:41:56.840 --> 01:42:02.080
[Guest]: Otherwise, you know, these institutions that Nehru built, a lot of things wouldn't have

01:42:02.080 --> 01:42:03.080
[Guest]: happened.

01:42:03.080 --> 01:42:04.080
[Guest]: But yes, this...

01:42:04.080 --> 01:42:09.120
[Guest]: Otherwise, what explains in 2014, this is a question that I've been asking a lot of

01:42:09.120 --> 01:42:15.560
[Guest]: people, I ask myself, this deep seated anger among suddenly you discover among your friends,

01:42:15.560 --> 01:42:20.440
[Guest]: your relatives whom you have known forever, where was this all this while?

01:42:20.440 --> 01:42:24.840
[Guest]: Why did it need 2014 election result for this kind of anger?

01:42:24.840 --> 01:42:31.120
[Guest]: There has to be very deep seated, you know, otherwise, now people don't even care when

01:42:31.120 --> 01:42:37.400
[Guest]: they abuse Muslims in drawing rooms or middle class drawing rooms or anywhere.

01:42:37.400 --> 01:42:38.400
[Guest]: It's no longer...

01:42:38.400 --> 01:42:42.800
[Guest]: I remember during Bajpayee's six years, it was not so blatant.

01:42:42.800 --> 01:42:44.860
[Guest]: It was, but not so blatant.

01:42:44.860 --> 01:42:45.960
[Guest]: Actually, there was no WhatsApp.

01:42:45.960 --> 01:42:46.960
[Amit Varma]: So we don't know.

01:42:46.960 --> 01:42:47.960
[Guest]: Can I attempt one theory?

01:42:47.960 --> 01:42:48.960
[Guest]: Please, please.

01:42:48.960 --> 01:42:49.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:42:49.960 --> 01:42:55.440
[Amit Varma]: So there's this sociologist called Timur Kuran, who in 98 or 99 wrote this book called Public

01:42:55.440 --> 01:42:58.200
[Amit Varma]: Lies and Private Truths, something of that sort.

01:42:58.200 --> 01:43:02.160
[Amit Varma]: And he came up with the phrase preference falsification, where he gave the example of

01:43:02.160 --> 01:43:06.280
[Amit Varma]: the Soviet Union, where he says that look, the Soviet Union appeared to fall overnight

01:43:06.280 --> 01:43:10.440
[Amit Varma]: as if the tide of public opinion changed suddenly, but it didn't happen like that.

01:43:10.440 --> 01:43:14.520
[Amit Varma]: What was happening was, everybody might have been against the government, but everybody

01:43:14.520 --> 01:43:19.480
[Amit Varma]: was afraid to speak out and they all thought they were alone, which is preference falsification.

01:43:19.480 --> 01:43:24.320
[Amit Varma]: And suddenly, there was a what he calls a preference cascade where people suddenly begin

01:43:24.320 --> 01:43:30.080
[Amit Varma]: to realize that everybody else is also things like them and that emboldens them and validates

01:43:30.080 --> 01:43:32.880
[Amit Varma]: their beliefs and then they can speak openly.

01:43:32.880 --> 01:43:38.480
[Amit Varma]: And I think what happened, and I've written about this as well, what happened in 2014

01:43:38.480 --> 01:43:43.000
[Amit Varma]: was, because of social media, the growth of social media in the five, six years before

01:43:43.000 --> 01:43:48.360
[Amit Varma]: that, a lot of people who I call closet bigots, but whatever, without using derogatory terms,

01:43:48.360 --> 01:43:53.840
[Amit Varma]: a lot of people who felt a certain way, but thought they should not say it in polite society,

01:43:53.840 --> 01:43:57.160
[Amit Varma]: suddenly realized, number one, that there are many, many more people who feel like that

01:43:57.160 --> 01:44:02.240
[Amit Varma]: to say it openly, that validates their beliefs, that emboldens them to speak out, and the

01:44:02.240 --> 01:44:04.200
[Amit Varma]: shoe is on the other foot.

01:44:04.200 --> 01:44:05.200
[Amit Varma]: And that's 24.

01:44:05.200 --> 01:44:06.200
[Guest]: I mean, that was just my take.

01:44:06.200 --> 01:44:10.400
[Guest]: No, no, that's absolutely, I entirely agree with this.

01:44:10.400 --> 01:44:13.440
[Guest]: But this, how did this happen?

01:44:13.440 --> 01:44:21.200
[Guest]: You know, this, like, you know, and this continued in 2019, for instance, everyone thought there'll

01:44:21.200 --> 01:44:24.800
[Guest]: be, you know, there'll be judged on performance.

01:44:24.800 --> 01:44:31.400
[Guest]: And as we were discussing before the recording, demonetization happened and not a protest

01:44:31.400 --> 01:44:36.600
[Guest]: that one knows of, you know, getting angry in a queue is not a protest, you know, that's

01:44:36.600 --> 01:44:40.760
[Guest]: it, Indians are used to getting angry when you're queuing at the airport or railway station

01:44:40.760 --> 01:44:43.200
[Guest]: anywhere or hospital.

01:44:43.200 --> 01:44:50.200
[Guest]: But, and it happened, it destroyed livelihoods, destroyed lives.

01:44:50.200 --> 01:44:52.200
[Guest]: Nothing matters to the people anymore.

01:44:52.200 --> 01:44:53.200
[Amit Varma]: And it's a triumph of narrative.

01:44:53.200 --> 01:44:57.120
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, it's a triumph of the Gita Press, triumph of Gita Press, you know, this

01:44:57.120 --> 01:45:02.880
[Guest]: is the kind of they were just saying things constantly, when they read it, not read it,

01:45:02.880 --> 01:45:08.640
[Guest]: you will see it, it's like the classic Coke ad, you know, they'll, when you go to watch

01:45:08.640 --> 01:45:15.520
[Guest]: the Hollywood movies in America, they'll say, drink Coke, eat popcorn, there was some catch

01:45:15.520 --> 01:45:17.720
[Guest]: line which I've forgotten.

01:45:17.720 --> 01:45:20.440
[Guest]: And they will do it so many times that you will, at the end of it, you'll say, I might

01:45:20.440 --> 01:45:22.800
[Guest]: as well go and have something, you know.

01:45:22.800 --> 01:45:29.240
[Guest]: So this constantly talking about cow, women, Muslim, the other, and when you place facts

01:45:29.240 --> 01:45:34.320
[Guest]: before people, you know, people, the class that you and I belong to, and tell them, tell

01:45:34.320 --> 01:45:39.320
[Guest]: me how many Muslims that you know, who have done extremely well in life, who have taken

01:45:39.320 --> 01:45:40.320
[Guest]: away your job.

01:45:40.320 --> 01:45:46.840
[Guest]: Damn it, I don't see Muslim kids in my kid's school, you know, how many Muslim kids that

01:45:46.840 --> 01:45:53.000
[Guest]: she has friends in school in college, how many Muslim friends I had, what are they taking

01:45:53.000 --> 01:45:54.000
[Amit Varma]: away then?

01:45:54.000 --> 01:45:59.080
[Amit Varma]: No, and there's like, like, I remember this incident with this friend of mine who's done

01:45:59.080 --> 01:46:03.240
[Amit Varma]: an MBA from a top school, has an absolute top job in the corporate sector.

01:46:03.240 --> 01:46:07.440
[Amit Varma]: And one day we were just chilling and he said that, Amit, there's one statistic which really

01:46:07.440 --> 01:46:09.240
[Amit Varma]: scares me and I said, what is it?

01:46:09.240 --> 01:46:14.600
[Amit Varma]: And he said, you know, the Hindu birth replacement rate is so and so and he takes 1.9 or something

01:46:14.600 --> 01:46:16.320
[Amit Varma]: and the Muslim rate is nine.

01:46:16.320 --> 01:46:17.760
[Amit Varma]: And I just started laughing.

01:46:17.760 --> 01:46:22.240
[Amit Varma]: I said that, bro, you know, this is not even something you need to fact check or Google

01:46:22.240 --> 01:46:23.240
[Unknown]: or whatever.

01:46:23.240 --> 01:46:31.280
[Amit Varma]: It's just common sense that this is complete rubbish and you find so many, and then you

01:46:31.280 --> 01:46:34.240
[Amit Varma]: think that, no, they're believing this because they want to believe this.

01:46:34.240 --> 01:46:35.600
[Guest]: They want to believe it.

01:46:35.600 --> 01:46:39.720
[Guest]: And when you place these facts, they're not, they will not agree, they'll say, no, how

01:46:39.720 --> 01:46:41.000
[Guest]: have you got this from?

01:46:41.000 --> 01:46:42.000
[Guest]: What is this from?

01:46:42.000 --> 01:46:47.560
[Guest]: You know, therefore, someone like say Pratik Sinha doing something which he does, it's

01:46:47.560 --> 01:46:48.920
[Guest]: like really hats off to him.

01:46:48.920 --> 01:46:49.920
[Amit Varma]: At great personal risk.

01:46:49.920 --> 01:46:50.920
[Unknown]: I mean, he's a hero.

01:46:50.920 --> 01:46:51.920
[Unknown]: Great personal risk.

01:46:51.920 --> 01:46:54.000
[Guest]: He's a great hero if you ask me.

01:46:54.000 --> 01:46:58.920
[Guest]: You know, a couple of times I have sent him a few things on Twitter, DMed him, you know,

01:46:58.920 --> 01:47:04.340
[Guest]: and I found that he figured this out and it was brought in public domain.

01:47:04.340 --> 01:47:07.000
[Guest]: But then again, how many people are on Twitter?

01:47:07.000 --> 01:47:13.320
[Guest]: It's the WhatsApp, which is the most dangerous, which is where all the religious jokes to

01:47:13.320 --> 01:47:17.840
[Guest]: everything and how quick they are with every failure which happens.

01:47:17.840 --> 01:47:23.080
[Guest]: Like that day, Chandrayan first attempted in go for purely scientific reasons, which

01:47:23.080 --> 01:47:27.640
[Guest]: is fine, what happens all over the world, but they took it in a completely different

01:47:27.640 --> 01:47:28.640
[Guest]: way.

01:47:28.640 --> 01:47:34.920
[Guest]: I got a few forwards which said, why this is, you know, this was, they gave it a new

01:47:34.920 --> 01:47:39.640
[Guest]: twist to it, which there's no business to do.

01:47:39.640 --> 01:47:43.400
[Guest]: And you will find that everyone and the enough takers for such narrative.

01:47:43.400 --> 01:47:49.960
[Amit Varma]: No, and also that depressing WhatsApp forward there was about so many countries have moons

01:47:49.960 --> 01:47:53.960
[Amit Varma]: and their flags, but we have a flag on the moon, at which point I'm thinking, what's

01:47:53.960 --> 01:47:54.960
[Amit Varma]: the point?

01:47:54.960 --> 01:47:57.840
[Guest]: You know, what are you going to do with the millions of jobless people in this country?

01:47:57.840 --> 01:47:58.840
[Guest]: You're going to send them?

01:47:58.840 --> 01:47:59.840
[Amit Varma]: Send them.

01:47:59.840 --> 01:48:01.320
[Amit Varma]: Nobody is worried about this.

01:48:01.320 --> 01:48:02.320
[Amit Varma]: It's insane.

01:48:02.320 --> 01:48:06.240
[Amit Varma]: To kind of get back to the subject of the Gita Press and politics, and you know, you

01:48:06.240 --> 01:48:10.440
[Amit Varma]: brought up the Hindu code bill a couple of times, and I do want to talk about that.

01:48:10.440 --> 01:48:14.600
[Amit Varma]: And I also want to talk about that, because there's a larger question I want to ask you,

01:48:14.600 --> 01:48:20.720
[Amit Varma]: which is a very difficult larger question, which is the relationship between the state

01:48:20.720 --> 01:48:21.720
[Amit Varma]: and society.

01:48:21.720 --> 01:48:22.720
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, right.

01:48:22.720 --> 01:48:28.280
[Amit Varma]: Like I had Rahul Verma, the political scientist on my show a while back, and he was talking

01:48:28.280 --> 01:48:33.320
[Amit Varma]: about one of the two ideological cleavages in India, we have different ideological cleavages

01:48:33.320 --> 01:48:36.680
[Amit Varma]: from the West, according to him, the left, right doesn't really apply here.

01:48:36.680 --> 01:48:40.920
[Amit Varma]: And one of those ideological cleavages is statism, that what is the role of the state

01:48:40.920 --> 01:48:42.720
[Amit Varma]: in relation to society.

01:48:42.720 --> 01:48:48.240
[Amit Varma]: And whereas the Western conception, the post enlightenment conception would be that, you

01:48:48.240 --> 01:48:52.960
[Amit Varma]: know, the state sort of you need the state for there to be society because someone's

01:48:52.960 --> 01:48:56.440
[Amit Varma]: got to protect your rights and blah, blah, blah.

01:48:56.440 --> 01:49:01.040
[Amit Varma]: But the Hindu conception, according to him, and the conception which all these Hindu nationalists

01:49:01.040 --> 01:49:05.880
[Amit Varma]: and the Gita Press people would share is that no society has existed from before.

01:49:05.880 --> 01:49:12.440
[Amit Varma]: The purpose of the state is to serve society, which to a certain degree even I agree with,

01:49:12.440 --> 01:49:16.760
[Amit Varma]: but the kind of society that I view where individual rights are protected, and so on

01:49:16.760 --> 01:49:19.560
[Amit Varma]: is completely different from these people's vision of it.

01:49:19.560 --> 01:49:25.840
[Amit Varma]: But nevertheless, their fundamental point is that our society is what it is for a reason,

01:49:25.840 --> 01:49:29.280
[Amit Varma]: and the state has no business interfering in it.

01:49:29.280 --> 01:49:33.960
[Amit Varma]: And this greater philosophical dilemma is what is again at the heart of the Hindu code

01:49:33.960 --> 01:49:35.120
[Amit Varma]: bill.

01:49:35.120 --> 01:49:36.280
[Amit Varma]: What do you think about this?

01:49:36.280 --> 01:49:42.280
[Guest]: Yes, in fact, Hindu code bill, I was talking to someone while researching that Hindu code

01:49:42.280 --> 01:49:50.400
[Guest]: bill and he said that, you know, the greatest suspicion which Hindus have, or at least this

01:49:50.400 --> 01:49:58.280
[Guest]: prominent Hindu groups, RSS or Vishwa Hindu Parishad or Mahasabha had at that point was

01:49:58.280 --> 01:50:03.040
[Guest]: and it Hindu code bill they faced successfully, see, the government managed to bring the bills

01:50:03.040 --> 01:50:08.080
[Guest]: eventually from broken into four, but they managed, the Hindu right groups managed to

01:50:08.080 --> 01:50:13.000
[Guest]: be this martyr, you know, why only this communities.

01:50:13.000 --> 01:50:20.480
[Guest]: So this narrative of state only trying to do something to Hindus, not to Muslims.

01:50:20.480 --> 01:50:26.160
[Guest]: So that is a great rejoice about what government has done more among Hindus than among Muslim

01:50:26.160 --> 01:50:31.640
[Guest]: women, I think, or this triple talaq, all the Muslim women I know, my friends, everyone

01:50:31.640 --> 01:50:37.320
[Amit Varma]: no one thinks that is such a big deal, you know, it's not relevant to them.

01:50:37.320 --> 01:50:41.240
[Guest]: But you find that Hindus are suddenly like more worried about Muslim women than anything

01:50:41.240 --> 01:50:42.240
[Guest]: else.

01:50:42.240 --> 01:50:47.600
[Guest]: They think it's you did this to us, state did this to us, the great secular state of

01:50:47.600 --> 01:50:49.800
[Guest]: Nehru did this to us in the 50s.

01:50:49.800 --> 01:50:51.600
[Guest]: So now it's your turn.

01:50:51.600 --> 01:50:56.600
[Guest]: And for whatever reason, they think triple talaq is the biggest problem facing Muslim

01:50:56.600 --> 01:50:57.960
[Guest]: women, which it is not.

01:50:57.960 --> 01:51:02.800
[Guest]: But anyway, so yes, they have a suspicion and they also have been very successfully

01:51:02.800 --> 01:51:08.040
[Guest]: managed to create, cultivate this thing that state has always been after them.

01:51:08.040 --> 01:51:14.600
[Guest]: And 60 years and the entire Congress rule, years of Congress rule as seen as basically

01:51:14.600 --> 01:51:18.920
[Guest]: anti-Hindu years, and which they have successfully.

01:51:18.920 --> 01:51:23.160
[Guest]: So every time, so Nehru has to be invoked, therefore, you know, what this happened the

01:51:23.160 --> 01:51:28.960
[Guest]: other day, Amit Shah is saying something about that in Kashmir.

01:51:28.960 --> 01:51:30.560
[Guest]: This happened because of Nehru.

01:51:30.560 --> 01:51:37.520
[Guest]: Then this, where Priyanka Gandhi went, Eastern UP, Yogi is saying, you know, this was done

01:51:37.520 --> 01:51:38.520
[Guest]: during Congress.

01:51:38.520 --> 01:51:39.520
[Guest]: So this is funny.

01:51:39.520 --> 01:51:41.520
[Amit Varma]: Now it's becoming absurd, actually, you know.

01:51:41.520 --> 01:51:46.080
[Amit Varma]: Nehru's actually, you forget Nehru, the real person, yeah, Nehru's become like a mythological

01:51:46.080 --> 01:51:47.080
[Unknown]: figure like Ravana.

01:51:47.080 --> 01:51:50.200
[Amit Varma]: I think in Dasarath, they'll put up a Nehru-

01:51:50.200 --> 01:51:54.040
[Guest]: Because there is a land dispute, someone goes and kills 10 Dalits.

01:51:54.040 --> 01:51:58.800
[Guest]: And you're saying because of what Congress rule did in between, you also ruled, BJP ruled

01:51:58.800 --> 01:52:01.560
[Guest]: for long, UP.

01:52:01.560 --> 01:52:03.800
[Amit Varma]: So this is becoming a bit comical, actually, now.

01:52:03.800 --> 01:52:08.120
[Amit Varma]: No, and honestly, look, what I would say is that there are a lot of criticisms that I

01:52:08.120 --> 01:52:11.240
[Amit Varma]: can level against Nehru's economic policies, the Congress government.

01:52:11.240 --> 01:52:13.240
[Guest]: He was full of his flaws, yeah, absolutely.

01:52:13.240 --> 01:52:17.280
[Amit Varma]: But this is just taking it to a new level, like you said, you know, you can't parody

01:52:17.280 --> 01:52:18.280
[Guest]: this shit.

01:52:18.280 --> 01:52:24.480
[Guest]: Now it's becoming a joke that some killing happens and then you're blaming Congress rule

01:52:24.480 --> 01:52:25.480
[Guest]: of the 50s.

01:52:25.480 --> 01:52:27.480
[Amit Varma]: Oh, what do you do?

01:52:27.480 --> 01:52:28.480
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:52:28.480 --> 01:52:33.600
[Amit Varma]: And another slightly, you know, and I found this very funny, you know, it was a hot button

01:52:33.600 --> 01:52:34.600
[Amit Varma]: once.

01:52:34.600 --> 01:52:35.600
[Amit Varma]: It's no longer a hot button.

01:52:35.600 --> 01:52:38.040
[Amit Varma]: But once upon a time, it was a hot button and a big cause for the Gita Press, which

01:52:38.040 --> 01:52:39.040
[Amit Varma]: is communism.

01:52:39.040 --> 01:52:46.320
[Guest]: Yeah, it was, it was, in fact, because directly, see, it was most prominent in Bengal.

01:52:46.320 --> 01:52:51.800
[Guest]: And that's where the Marwadi's, the good old Marwadi world existed in Calcutta, shift to

01:52:51.800 --> 01:52:53.160
[Guest]: Bombay happened much later.

01:52:53.160 --> 01:52:59.040
[Guest]: In fact, even now, some of the big Marwadi companies still have work out of, they dominate

01:52:59.040 --> 01:53:00.040
[Amit Varma]: Calcutta.

01:53:00.040 --> 01:53:01.040
[Unknown]: They dominate even now.

01:53:01.040 --> 01:53:03.800
[Guest]: And they even fund films in Bombay from there.

01:53:03.800 --> 01:53:07.760
[Guest]: So, and this was a real challenge.

01:53:07.760 --> 01:53:12.360
[Guest]: And you have to give it to them, they figured this out much before.

01:53:12.360 --> 01:53:20.680
[Guest]: In fact, they were, they were having this two part series article on Samevaad in Russia

01:53:20.680 --> 01:53:26.640
[Guest]: and all kinds of, and somehow, again, this some deprivation you need to bring it everything

01:53:26.640 --> 01:53:31.960
[Guest]: down to women, you know, they'll say, yeh communism mein sabse zyada problem mahilaon

01:53:31.960 --> 01:53:33.240
[Guest]: ke saath hota hai.

01:53:33.240 --> 01:53:36.920
[Guest]: And then they will say that one woman has to have a relationship with 20 men, all kinds

01:53:36.920 --> 01:53:41.880
[Guest]: of absurd, unfounded, you know, women exist for society.

01:53:41.880 --> 01:53:44.960
[Guest]: So anyone can have any kind of relationship with women.

01:53:44.960 --> 01:53:51.920
[Guest]: So I think they realized that this immediately strikes a chord among the readers of people

01:53:51.920 --> 01:53:56.440
[Guest]: that, you know, this is what the new ideology is all about.

01:53:56.440 --> 01:54:02.200
[Guest]: And they were early on to realize that this is going to create problem for them in Bengal.

01:54:02.200 --> 01:54:06.760
[Guest]: Because Bengal forever has been, you know, right from the beginning of the 20th century,

01:54:06.760 --> 01:54:10.040
[Guest]: even before that, Marwadis have been there in Bengal.

01:54:10.040 --> 01:54:17.280
[Guest]: So you have to, they figured out, built good alliance with RSS groups, others, even saying

01:54:17.280 --> 01:54:21.800
[Guest]: in one letter, they're saying that we have to learn from the this communists also, how

01:54:21.800 --> 01:54:23.680
[Guest]: they do this pamphlets.

01:54:23.680 --> 01:54:28.120
[Guest]: So we have to do the pamphlets, we have to learn and do similar thing, otherwise, we'll

01:54:28.120 --> 01:54:29.120
[Amit Varma]: be finished.

01:54:29.120 --> 01:54:35.680
[Amit Varma]: And the recent results in Lok Sabha elections, you know, you mentioned the views of communism

01:54:35.680 --> 01:54:37.240
[Amit Varma]: and how that went to women.

