[Amit Varma]: In Marxism, since everything was state owned, there was no need for a woman to be in a relationship

01:55:23.040 --> 01:55:24.360
[Amit Varma]: with one man.

01:55:24.360 --> 01:55:29.360
[Amit Varma]: As there were no laws of inheritance and private ownership of property, Karpatri said, a woman

01:55:29.360 --> 01:55:34.880
[Amit Varma]: became like a bucket of water that could quench the thirst of many men, stop quote.

01:55:34.880 --> 01:55:37.640
[Amit Varma]: This is how they used to write.

01:55:37.640 --> 01:55:39.800
[Guest]: And then this man is absolutely revered by.

01:55:39.800 --> 01:55:40.800
[Guest]: He is revered.

01:55:40.800 --> 01:55:45.400
[Guest]: No, but he became a bit of a, later years, he became a liability.

01:55:45.400 --> 01:55:51.960
[Guest]: In fact, he was, he wanted his whole take was in the rural economy, a very regressive

01:55:51.960 --> 01:55:52.960
[Guest]: rural economy.

01:55:52.960 --> 01:55:55.440
[Guest]: Even Jansang, beyond a point, dumped him.

01:55:55.440 --> 01:55:59.800
[Guest]: I think he did well in the first election for, he got some six, seven seats, he got

01:55:59.800 --> 01:56:00.800
[Guest]: few seats.

01:56:00.800 --> 01:56:06.560
[Guest]: Then two elections he did, and then slowly he sank, and this book itself is hilarious.

01:56:06.560 --> 01:56:11.040
[Guest]: It's a fat volume, which I consider a lot of people have been asking me to lend me a

01:56:11.040 --> 01:56:12.040
[Guest]: volume.

01:56:12.040 --> 01:56:13.040
[Guest]: Lend me this volume.

01:56:13.040 --> 01:56:14.040
[Amit Varma]: I said, only if you promise to return it.

01:56:14.040 --> 01:56:15.040
[Amit Varma]: Is it an English translation?

01:56:15.040 --> 01:56:22.480
[Guest]: In fact, I had asked Gita Press people, they said, no, nobody translates.

01:56:22.480 --> 01:56:29.800
[Guest]: I can, I don't know who will have the guts to, it's a fat volume, going in all directions.

01:56:29.800 --> 01:56:34.680
[Amit Varma]: And another thing I found very funny was how the Gita Press then strategizes that they

01:56:34.680 --> 01:56:38.680
[Amit Varma]: are going to co-opt communism, and they're going to contrast Russian communism with an

01:56:38.680 --> 01:56:43.520
[Amit Varma]: Indian communism, which they claimed originated in Hinduism.

01:56:43.520 --> 01:56:47.640
[Amit Varma]: And I'm again going to quote a delightful book from your book, where you say, quote,

01:56:47.640 --> 01:56:51.480
[Amit Varma]: two similarities were noted between Indian and Russian communisms.

01:56:51.480 --> 01:56:54.960
[Amit Varma]: The first would delight even the most serious of political theorists.

01:56:54.960 --> 01:57:00.680
[Amit Varma]: It said that Lord Krishna, the originator of Indian communism, dallied with Gopis, hardworking

01:57:00.680 --> 01:57:05.200
[Amit Varma]: milkmaids, just as the fathers of Russian communism were involved with humble peasants

01:57:05.200 --> 01:57:06.200
[Amit Varma]: and workers.

01:57:06.200 --> 01:57:10.200
[Amit Varma]: The second similarity was more to the point, both versions were aimed at the betterment

01:57:10.200 --> 01:57:14.200
[Amit Varma]: of the poor and downtrodden, stop quote.

01:57:14.200 --> 01:57:20.200
[Amit Varma]: And then another writer called Charu Chandramitra argued that the basic mantra of communism

01:57:20.200 --> 01:57:25.160
[Amit Varma]: from each according to his ability, to each according to his need, was already practiced

01:57:25.160 --> 01:57:29.880
[Amit Varma]: in India through the joint family system.

01:57:29.880 --> 01:57:35.000
[Guest]: But you have to give it to them for trying at least, they were trying to get onto, for

01:57:35.000 --> 01:57:40.360
[Guest]: a religious journal to be aware of this danger, although the way they dealt with this danger

01:57:40.360 --> 01:57:46.200
[Guest]: is very funny and very unscholarly, but that's how they were, you know.

01:57:46.200 --> 01:57:52.840
[Guest]: But for them it was really, in fact, see this side of Poddar, which I wanted to write more,

01:57:52.840 --> 01:58:01.640
[Guest]: I found few instances, he had also become a big figure in matters of business for Marwadis.

01:58:01.640 --> 01:58:08.680
[Guest]: For instance, when this whole Dalmia cement and ACC thing is happening, everyone is asking

01:58:08.680 --> 01:58:17.520
[Guest]: him to intervene, because ACC was a big MNC coming, it would have destroyed Dalmia cement.

01:58:17.520 --> 01:58:24.800
[Guest]: And what he does is he somehow, he plays some role, whereby they come together, actually

01:58:24.800 --> 01:58:30.040
[Guest]: that becomes it's a, so it becomes Dalmia ACC, they create a joint group rather than

01:58:30.040 --> 01:58:31.040
[Amit Varma]: fighting with each other.

01:58:31.040 --> 01:58:32.040
[Amit Varma]: He's like an elder statesman.

01:58:32.040 --> 01:58:33.880
[Guest]: Yeah, he's an elder statesman.

01:58:33.880 --> 01:58:38.720
[Guest]: And much later also, even when you find the Dalmia, he was very closely associated with

01:58:38.720 --> 01:58:40.880
[Guest]: Dalmia family.

01:58:40.880 --> 01:58:48.000
[Guest]: Even small matters, when the entire separation took place, Times of India, Jains moved out

01:58:48.000 --> 01:58:55.560
[Guest]: from the father-in-law Dalmia, Sao Santiprasad Jain, and the matter went to court, the Vivian

01:58:55.560 --> 01:59:02.840
[Guest]: Commission report, they say that it is a limited company, it's a listed company.

01:59:02.840 --> 01:59:08.040
[Guest]: And they're completely disregarding the shareholders, they're taking all the decisions.

01:59:08.040 --> 01:59:12.960
[Guest]: And they're saying, how did you take the decision, they're saying, because Bhaiji told us.

01:59:12.960 --> 01:59:19.320
[Guest]: And Bhaiji is saying them in a very, you know, good old Baniya way of dividing property or

01:59:19.320 --> 01:59:23.760
[Guest]: business, which is not entirely yours, you have shareholders, you know, you're answerable

01:59:23.760 --> 01:59:25.600
[Guest]: to them.

01:59:25.600 --> 01:59:31.800
[Guest]: And so he was playing a big role even in that Vivian Bose Commission report is full of Podare

01:59:31.800 --> 01:59:33.120
[Guest]: actually.

01:59:33.120 --> 01:59:36.860
[Guest]: So this man had his foot everywhere, you know.

01:59:36.860 --> 01:59:42.000
[Amit Varma]: So here's a question that kind of strikes me and tell me what you think of this.

01:59:42.000 --> 01:59:46.840
[Amit Varma]: My observation when I finished the book and contextualizing it to the current times, was

01:59:46.840 --> 01:59:51.800
[Amit Varma]: that for much of the last few decades, the movement at the Gita Press was spearheading

01:59:51.800 --> 01:59:55.960
[Amit Varma]: with the alliance that it built together of all the Hindu groups, Mahasabha RSS and so

01:59:55.960 --> 01:59:56.960
[Amit Varma]: on.

01:59:56.960 --> 02:00:01.960
[Amit Varma]: So the movement that it was spearheading had success within the culture, but not within

02:00:01.960 --> 02:00:02.960
[Amit Varma]: politics.

02:00:02.960 --> 02:00:05.560
[Amit Varma]: It was a cultural success, but not a political success.

02:00:05.560 --> 02:00:11.240
[Amit Varma]: And I'm just wondering whether today that they've gained this enormous political success,

02:00:11.240 --> 02:00:16.560
[Amit Varma]: there is also a slight cultural downswing because of the dual forces of globalization

02:00:16.560 --> 02:00:17.560
[Amit Varma]: and urbanization.

02:00:17.560 --> 02:00:23.060
[Amit Varma]: That while it may seem that okay, the project has succeeded, could it be said that actually

02:00:23.060 --> 02:00:28.040
[Amit Varma]: culturally as we become more and more exposed to the globe, as we are say incorporating

02:00:28.040 --> 02:00:32.920
[Amit Varma]: hip hop in a film like Gully Boy, or as more and more people are getting aspirational in

02:00:32.920 --> 02:00:35.200
[Amit Varma]: different ways than they would earlier.

02:00:35.200 --> 02:00:41.920
[Amit Varma]: And as more and more of India is urbanizing, which, you know, tends to put people together,

02:00:41.920 --> 02:00:46.160
[Amit Varma]: more squeezed together and less likely to discriminate because they are part of those

02:00:46.160 --> 02:00:48.760
[Amit Varma]: economic networks for self interest.

02:00:48.760 --> 02:00:55.720
[Amit Varma]: And again, I'm just completely speculating, and I think you'd be better off.

02:00:55.720 --> 02:01:01.440
[Guest]: I'm not really sure whether, see, all this has happened, but how do you kind of explain

02:01:01.440 --> 02:01:06.560
[Guest]: some of these people who also do, I'm just giving an example of a friend, I don't want

02:01:06.560 --> 02:01:14.480
[Guest]: to name him, who is completely postmodern in his, when it comes to his choice of music,

02:01:14.480 --> 02:01:22.120
[Guest]: or even some bit of literature, but extremely conservative, and I've asked him.

02:01:22.120 --> 02:01:26.000
[Guest]: And he said that it coexists.

02:01:26.000 --> 02:01:34.720
[Guest]: For instance, how does one explain the grand success of Article 15, okay, and Kabir, what

02:01:34.720 --> 02:01:35.720
[Guest]: is that movie?

02:01:35.720 --> 02:01:36.720
[Guest]: Kabir Singh.

02:01:36.720 --> 02:01:37.720
[Guest]: Kabir Singh.

02:01:37.720 --> 02:01:41.600
[Guest]: So I was telling this friend of mine, he said, you know, both of them have made money.

02:01:41.600 --> 02:01:44.080
[Guest]: What is happening to our society?

02:01:44.080 --> 02:01:49.040
[Guest]: Article 15 also made money, it's a successful movie, which is very serious movie.

02:01:49.040 --> 02:01:54.000
[Guest]: Well, a lot of my Dalit activist friends are upset over other reasons, which is fine, which

02:01:54.000 --> 02:01:55.000
[Amit Varma]: one can argue.

02:01:55.000 --> 02:02:00.320
[Guest]: But as a mainstream film, it has done very well.

02:02:00.320 --> 02:02:07.760
[Guest]: And it almost coincided with Kabir Singh, which is supposed to be kind of a money spinner

02:02:07.760 --> 02:02:09.960
[Guest]: made some 200 crores.

02:02:09.960 --> 02:02:10.960
[Guest]: So what is happening to society?

02:02:10.960 --> 02:02:16.960
[Guest]: I don't know, we're becoming more cosmopolitan, global, as you said.

02:02:16.960 --> 02:02:23.000
[Guest]: But it's like, one of my other friends says that it's an NRI phenomena, which is now we

02:02:23.000 --> 02:02:28.520
[Guest]: see more here, you know, you want to make your money working for the MNCs, but when

02:02:28.520 --> 02:02:33.840
[Guest]: it comes to vote, you want to vote for a guy who is like socially conservative, God knows

02:02:33.840 --> 02:02:34.840
[Guest]: what he does.

02:02:34.840 --> 02:02:37.960
[Guest]: So this is some bit of it is happening here.

02:02:37.960 --> 02:02:43.480
[Guest]: Otherwise, you know, let's just look at all the NRI crowd, you know, all of us have NRI

02:02:43.480 --> 02:02:49.360
[Guest]: relatives who are like, completely vouching for completely conservative politics.

02:02:49.360 --> 02:02:52.800
[Guest]: If they had their way, Pakistan would not exist.

02:02:52.800 --> 02:02:56.000
[Guest]: They're sitting in New York or sitting in London is very easy for them.

02:02:56.000 --> 02:02:59.400
[Guest]: It would spontaneously combust.

02:02:59.400 --> 02:03:06.080
[Guest]: So I really don't know how this these things are happening to a society we are becoming.

02:03:06.080 --> 02:03:12.440
[Guest]: So culturally, this project, as you said, there is a downslide to it, there's a down.

02:03:12.440 --> 02:03:15.160
[Guest]: Maybe it will happen, because it has to happen.

02:03:15.160 --> 02:03:19.400
[Guest]: Because in the last five years, we've seen nothing and we have been seeing it even otherwise.

02:03:19.400 --> 02:03:25.280
[Guest]: But now, past five years have been very pronounced on your face, like, we have, we are there,

02:03:25.280 --> 02:03:28.160
[Guest]: you take it, you have no choice, you leave it.

02:03:28.160 --> 02:03:33.720
[Guest]: As someone other day said that, you know, this Guardian article on Turkish intellectuals

02:03:33.720 --> 02:03:41.800
[Guest]: of what they did, just simply said your time is over, you know, to that good old, now bad

02:03:41.800 --> 02:03:43.840
[Guest]: word called liberals.

02:03:43.840 --> 02:03:46.120
[Guest]: Similar thing is happening in India.

02:03:46.120 --> 02:03:55.120
[Guest]: But for how long, whether this will continue, whether people will forget their jobs, their

02:03:55.120 --> 02:04:01.680
[Guest]: other things, and continue to be part of this project and vote for a party which only talks

02:04:01.680 --> 02:04:05.080
[Guest]: of religion, talks of segregation, talks of hate.

02:04:05.080 --> 02:04:07.400
[Amit Varma]: I don't know.

02:04:07.400 --> 02:04:12.240
[Amit Varma]: What you said is really thought provoking in terms of Article 15 and Kabir Singh both

02:04:12.240 --> 02:04:13.240
[Amit Varma]: doing well.

02:04:13.240 --> 02:04:16.880
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that it doesn't mean that in this large country with millions of people

02:04:16.880 --> 02:04:19.760
[Amit Varma]: that entirely different audiences watch those two films.

02:04:19.760 --> 02:04:24.480
[Amit Varma]: I think there must be many people who watch both films and like them for different reasons.

02:04:24.480 --> 02:04:25.480
[Amit Varma]: Like them for different reasons.

02:04:25.480 --> 02:04:26.480
[Amit Varma]: Because people contain multiple views.

02:04:26.480 --> 02:04:27.480
[Guest]: It's completely Foxpeel.

02:04:27.480 --> 02:04:30.760
[Guest]: How is this, both the movies doing well?

02:04:30.760 --> 02:04:35.680
[Amit Varma]: Because I guess, if I'm again thinking aloud, and maybe this is simplistic, but Kabir Singh

02:04:35.680 --> 02:04:40.160
[Amit Varma]: might appeal to certain impulses that people have.

02:04:40.160 --> 02:04:44.920
[Amit Varma]: And Article 15 may appeal to the more rational side of, and obviously what people like you

02:04:44.920 --> 02:04:49.840
[Amit Varma]: and me hope for is that the rationality wins out in the long run.

02:04:49.840 --> 02:04:55.440
[Amit Varma]: So I'll end this episode by asking you a question I ask many of my guests on whatever subject

02:04:55.440 --> 02:05:01.680
[Amit Varma]: we're discussing, that looking into the future, and I normally say 10 years, but in this case,

02:05:01.680 --> 02:05:04.880
[Amit Varma]: because you know, your book has covered a century and all of that, I'll give it a slightly

02:05:04.880 --> 02:05:06.100
[Amit Varma]: longer span.

02:05:06.100 --> 02:05:10.840
[Amit Varma]: Looking into the future over the next 20 years, what gives you despair and what gives you

02:05:10.840 --> 02:05:14.240
[Amit Varma]: hope about the state of Indian society?

02:05:14.240 --> 02:05:16.920
[Guest]: First, the despair.

02:05:16.920 --> 02:05:26.560
[Guest]: My despair is, biggest despair is that our institutions will be destroyed beyond redemption

02:05:26.560 --> 02:05:27.560
[Guest]: so badly.

02:05:27.560 --> 02:05:31.920
[Guest]: And when I talk of institution, I don't mean one university here, one university there,

02:05:31.920 --> 02:05:37.800
[Guest]: the larger fabric of the way we discuss, the Supreme Court, the RBI, you know, and the

02:05:37.800 --> 02:05:44.880
[Guest]: discourse, the narrative, the institution, the discourse, discourse for all time to come,

02:05:44.880 --> 02:05:50.120
[Guest]: I think it's vitiated for a long, long time, and it's not going to go away so easily.

02:05:50.120 --> 02:05:56.440
[Guest]: You have poison, and I talked to my daughter also, who's 18 year old university going girl,

02:05:56.440 --> 02:06:03.080
[Guest]: and she tells me things which is not, at times, it gives me great, it makes me very, very

02:06:03.080 --> 02:06:04.080
[Guest]: despair.

02:06:04.080 --> 02:06:10.000
[Guest]: But then I also see bookstores, I see, I meet people who are worried, I meet very young

02:06:10.000 --> 02:06:16.160
[Guest]: students, again, at the same time, who tell you that they don't approve, you go for, lit

02:06:16.160 --> 02:06:23.200
[Guest]: fest might not be the exact answer to say, because these are happening in very urban

02:06:23.200 --> 02:06:28.040
[Guest]: spaces, these are children who brought up in a very different way.

02:06:28.040 --> 02:06:32.800
[Guest]: But even in small towns, I've been to a few small towns also, and I see there's some bit

02:06:32.800 --> 02:06:39.960
[Guest]: of, in the long run, I think the constitution, to sum it up, in the long run, I think, you

02:06:39.960 --> 02:06:46.280
[Guest]: know, the constitution will be upheld, we will, and the institutional, for instance,

02:06:46.280 --> 02:06:51.400
[Guest]: media, this can't go on for long, nobody will read you, media also knows, media has lost

02:06:51.400 --> 02:06:58.280
[Guest]: its credibility, while serving one party, certain government, they've lost the credibility.

02:06:58.280 --> 02:07:05.160
[Guest]: So I, and at the same time, even the mainstream media has failed, you have a parallel media,

02:07:05.160 --> 02:07:10.440
[Guest]: which has given us hope, which is, and what will be without hope, you know, and we have

02:07:10.440 --> 02:07:16.240
[Guest]: seen societies around us, we have not suffered as much as Pakistan has suffered, or Turkey

02:07:16.240 --> 02:07:19.400
[Guest]: is suffering or various other states.

02:07:19.400 --> 02:07:24.160
[Guest]: So and they've come out of it in various ways, they fought, so I'm sure people will fight.

02:07:24.160 --> 02:07:28.840
[Guest]: This can't go on, this, this, this sarad of nationalism, this whole thing will not go

02:07:28.840 --> 02:07:29.840
[Amit Varma]: on.

02:07:29.840 --> 02:07:31.640
[Guest]: And our Khichri is a resilient Khichri.

02:07:31.640 --> 02:07:35.160
[Guest]: Yeah, our Khichri is a resilient Khichri, it has to survive.

02:07:35.160 --> 02:07:37.480
[Guest]: That's the only way we can survive, you know, all of us.

02:07:37.480 --> 02:07:40.560
[Amit Varma]: Akshay, I'm so honoured that you gave me so much of your time today.

02:07:40.560 --> 02:07:41.560
[Guest]: Thank you so much for coming.

02:07:41.560 --> 02:07:43.680
[Guest]: It was a real pleasure, Amit, talking to you.

